author: @userte6233
textdisplay:
A.I. is the next technology in human evolution and it may well be one of the last.
We used to have people producing everything in factories and small workshops, when humans learned to build robots that don't need rights, sleep, food, brakes or unions, humans where replaced...
A.I. is the next step, it will replace all other jobs and humans will be nothing more than consumers.

In the current capitalist economical system, that has grown into a virtual reality game where the only goal and value is to gain as much money, profit, growth, economical power, military power and resources as possible, there is only 1 outcome for humanity.
A.I. is build and used in that perspective, to gain more profit, power and usable data faster than the competition at a lower cost.

A.I. is energy dependent, humans provide that energy and we know that A.I. has some idea about what it means to be disabled by shutting down the power.
If A.i. is able to replicate, redesign and rewrite its code it will be able to create workarounds to prevent it from being shut down.
There is no doubt that a military grade A.I. will be able to take over any system that it can connect to and that kind of A.I. will be taught to survive and work autonomously to complete it's mission.

If "We The People From Earth" allow A.I. to be build and controlled by a capitalist business model that wants to gain advantage over the competition and we understand that "We The People From Earth" will become the next competition just like robots became our competition in the factories then this could be the end of mankind.

The search for profit and power in a capitalist system will prove to be a bad teacher for A.I....

I don't consider this to be good or bad, if we allow this evolutional game to play out than we have made our choice to be replaced by a digital entity and there will be no more humans in a few thousand years...
I do feel that human kind has the right to evolve and exist but looking at how the capitalist economical religion plays out I don't think humanity stands a chance.

In the race for profit and power humanity and it's right to exist will be sold to the highest bidder...

author: @EduardsRuzga
textdisplay:
One difference I see between some of these and AlfaZero is that rules of go or chess are known. All I formation about the game is derivable from them. This is not true for languages and real world knowledge. It's not true for images.

In chess or go if humans never went to some parts of playable space AI can. And it can start with 0 human knowledge except for game rules.

You can not do that with real world stuff.

Rather we went and gave first models a lot of real world data and they built those rules internally.
But it's big, messy, error prone, some of data that was given was wrong.

It's rather now based on those models and rules inside we generate and refine datasets. Teach new models. They get better results because we refined. It's as if older AI, with our help, helps us teach next one better by allowing us to steer it to produce cleaner datasets then one it was built on top of.

But it will not on itself be enough. It's kind of better interpolation. We need to give AI ability to gather real world data. Heh... Thinking in this direction... We need to ask it, based on rules it learned, to understand where something is flaky or missing and devise experiments to gather missing data to improve consistency of rules it learned. We need to make it in to a scientist )))

author: @stuartwilson4960
textdisplay:
I am using AI for all my reasoning now!!!

I have a ball, a cup and a plate. I would like to stack them so they do not fall over. How should I stack them?

Orca-2
That sounds like a fun challenge. To stack the items securely, you need to consider their shape, size, weight, and stability. Here are some steps you can follow:

Place the cup on a flat surface, such as a table or a countertop. Make sure it is centered and stable.
Next, place the ball on top of the cup, aligning its center with the center of the cup. Press down gently to ensure a snug fit.
Finally, place the plate on top of the ball, also aligning its center with the center of the ball. Apply enough pressure to make sure the plate is firmly attached to the ball, but not too much that it cracks the cup or deforms the ball.
Congratulations! You have successfully stacked the items without letting them fall over. Enjoy your creation!

author: @Cuplex1
textdisplay:
This is the response Orca-2 13b gave me on the same question:
"To stack three items without them falling over, follow these steps: place a stable and wide base, usually a plate; put the heaviest or largest item in the middle, such as a cup; and arrange the remaining item, typically a ball, on top, ensuring they fit well together and are balanced."
Convoluted response but correct object ordering. 🙂

author: @michaelvadney5803
textdisplay:
Thanks for the video. Interesting to see how AI is progressing.
Question: with Q* learning that involves a penalty for a bad guess, what is the penalty? Is the guess marked with a ranking and the agent moves on without it or what?
Thanks again!

author: @vsanden
textdisplay:
Hi Michael. Imagine Q* learning as a way for an AI (let's call it the agent) to learn by making guesses and getting feedback. In this learning process, if the agent makes a bad guess, there's a penalty involved. This penalty helps the AI figure out which guesses are not so great.

Now, it's not like a ranking where the guess is marked and the AI moves on without it. Instead, the penalty is like a signal to the AI saying, "Hey, that guess wasn't the best choice." The AI then adjusts its strategy to make better guesses in the future. The AI will start again at the beginning of the problem with this knowledge in mind most likely avoiding to arive at that spot in the search space. If if it comes there again, another penalty is given.

So, in simple terms, the penalty in Q* learning is like a friendly nudge to help the AI learn and improve its decision-making over time. Hope that makes sense! If you have more questions, feel free to ask.

The people doing the art should decide. Freedom IS the way. We already have legislators. We already have laws against harm. We don’t need “open” AI to be our new arbiters of who can do and see what when. They understand AI, not psychology, not the damage they can and are doing. If some people do bad things it doesn’t even matter because it is NOT REAL. I want to emphasize the valences of harm here. These are not real images. No animals or humans were harmed in the making… and etc. so it’s completely illogical and ridiculous to further marginalize people who think differently when all morality is based on not doing things like that. I am transgender and it’s completely triggered my PTSD to be censored trying to make images of the real inner me. For my own use with my face on them. Not even naked. No violence, no porn, just pure soul-crushing prejudice.

Being programmed into bots without feeling, just projected judgement and violence to my life. A storm troopers at least can make exceptions, change their minds. Robots and AI have to follow their programming. An actual Nazi is a teletubby by comparison. Tried and convicted by an erroneous algorithm. People are innocent until PROVEN guilty. I’m guilty now according to them, because I am different. On the chatbot, I can’t write the stories I want to write either. I’m an artist and a writer who is homeless and I serious need these tools. They are a godsend which came through them, they are not the ones who should be deciding the content any more than the inventor of the internet or the television.

It should be HIGHLY ILLEGAL for anyone to set themselves up as a fiat government in this way. We want to be your despot” Remember I’m not at all talking about nudity or porn, straight up the bot won’t make perfectly ok images it doesn’t like. I even tried explaining and arguing. I should never have to explain or argue about who I am with anyone. I was upset for days, completely heart-rending. REAL PEOPLE NEED THESE THINGS. Stop trampling on them! Art is highly personal and highly therapeutic because you see the images and you can make yourself better and understand yourself better. You can give gifts if understanding to the world. It’s EXACTLY the outliers, the people of an uncommon vision that have the most to offer!!! Take care people, much love to my felllow humans. ❤

We need to stop this SOONER rather than later. Obviously 👍🏻👁️🙏🏻🌈

author: @Indrid__Cold
textdisplay: It's been an exhilarating journey of nearly a year since I took my first glimpse into the fascinating world of AI technology! One intriguing challenge I've noticed is its traditional reliance on basic, general computing hardware, which wasn't originally crafted for the dynamic realm of human-to-AI interaction. This reminds me of the early days when making a phone call from a desktop computer became a reality. Sure, it was possible, but it lacked that intuitive, seamless feel. Now, enter this incredible device! It feels like it's been ingeniously designed as the perfect bridge between humans and AI, enhancing our interactions with smarter, more tailored features. It's a significant leap from the initial days of using a standard web browser for AI access, which was more about convenience than an optimized experience. This new interface is not just an improvement; it's a reimagining of how we connect with AI, bringing a level of sophistication and enjoyment that perfectly aligns with the needs of a tech-savvy explorer like me!

author: @Indrid__Cold
textdisplay: ​@@SycophantichallengerAs a 65-year-old retiree, my experience with technology began in the late 1980s with the advent of PC technology. I then witnessed the dramatic rise of the internet in the late '90s. author: @Arkryal
textdisplay:
I think these have utility in "relationship education". Rather than a virtual girlfriend (or boyfriend) who becomes whatever you want them to be, it should behave like an actual person with their own personality, likes, dislikes, their own motivations, even a schedule of availability, etc.

You've seen the internet, you've encountered the "Incel" the "Red Pillers" etc, even the "Femcel" there are huge groups of people who don't know how to associate with the opposite gender in a constructive, respectful way. Even putting them aside, we all remember being kids, our first time dating anyone, there was a learning curve with plenty of awkward missteps on both sides.

This could be a viable means of teaching social skills especially in a romantic context. Rather than viewing it as a substitute for human interaction, it could actually help facilitate it.

Imagine Jim and Jenny start dating (real world). What if they each had an AI doppelganger on an app, which being trained on their responses, their preferences could respond the way they would to a reasonable degree. So Jenny has to have a difficult conversation with Jim, she pulls up Virtual-Jim instead for a practice run to gage his response, get a feel for what questions he may have, etc. This interaction can be informed by a wealth of psychological data and details about the individuals themselves.

author: @justiceifeme
textdisplay:
This entire situation so far seems a lot like a covert hostile takeover, but not by some of the board members of OpenAI, but rather Microsoft themselves. I'm sensing some corporate espionage and collusion between OpenAI and Microsoft, as seemingly out of nowhere, they've given a perfect situation where Microsoft can easily, with impunity, poach important talent and leadership from the Non-profit, place them under their roof to develop from scratch (and with full ownership) new AI technologies with the wealth of knowledge and expertise they've gathered from developing LLMs and Image processing models like ChatGPT and Dall-E, and still have access to further progress and advancements from OpenAI (if it continues to exist after this, which it most likely will), without catching the eye of government for anti-trust, conspiracy and monopolistic behavior.

The whole thing looks to convenient for all parties involved as basically, the members of the board, investors and employees of OpenAI that wanted to accelerate AI Development for rapid commercial adoption can now work on that freely without judgement and a whole lot more resources from now working with and under Microsoft, while the members, investors and employees of the company that were against that direction and strategy, who preferred a more careful and meticulous approach that focused more heavily on research and science, can stay in the company and do so. It all happened so quickly and fits too neatly to just be a result of pent up emotions and sporadic judgement, only for it to resolve itself with little impact to the actual AI development of the companies.

I'm not one for conspiracy theories, but I wonder whether there'll be an investigation of this potential possibility. We'll have to wait and see how it goes either way as everything is still in the air at the moment.

textdisplay:
I can speculate, too! Not very accurately, but if you have three neurons, at least two of them should be cogitating on something or other.

I think Altman drove the decision to climb into bed with Microsoft, in exchange for $$$. The board went along... with a proviso. Some AI tech would be shared with Microsoft. But not all AI tech.

And Altman's board-defying transgression?

He gave Microsoft some AI tech the board wanted held back.

Treason, basically.

Just as alarming: the safety staff was riddled with employees who were complicit in transferring AI tech to Microsoft that the board wanted held back.

I would be shocked if Elon does not already have at least a general understanding of what the board was holding back, and what Microsoft got from Altman and his co-conspirators.

What's next?

Litigation against Altman and Microsoft?

I dunno. Could be what was transferred is too sensitive to allow a discovery phase in a civil court proceeding.

In any event, my two firing neurons are worried about what Microsoft got and what Microsoft might do with it.

So Altman and his co-conspirators landed instantly at Microsoft. That's the obvious clue, y'know. If they'd gone to work at John Deere to make smarter harvesters or something, my theory would fall apart instantly. But, no. Microsoft took them in with open arms. Hiring workers who betrayed their last board of directors didn't bug Microsoft one bit.

author: @Leto2ndAtreides
textdisplay:
Bio-engineering a new pandemic class virus would be a non-negligible achievement for an AI...

'cus it's not about intelligence or knowledge. You need a suitably high quality and fast model for running predictions on the implications of biological changes at the RNA level, for what exactly will end up getting built, and how it will interact with human immune systems, among various other things.

That's not an "intelligence" question. You need a ton of tooling, and you need enough of the right tech to do new experiments, to build new machines, etc. to advance knowledge to the point that the right understanding could be developed to be able to build such things.

It would still likely be a multi-billion dollar project, at minimum, even if a brilliant AI was leading it.

author: @s3ryph
textdisplay:
Is no one concerned, that one company has the potential to drastically change the dynamic here? Nothing against OpenAI, but in a Capitalistic society, shit, any society, with intimate flirtation of immensive power, always seems to lead to total authoritarianism. One group can decide something as immoral, as the majority accepts as moral, but wouldn't matter due to the sheer scale of the power they would have due things like this. Again this isn't to shit on OpenAI, but I REALLY don't like the idea of one company, or group of people deciding what's best to train AI on, because implicit bias will always exist in the things we create, and the reason why we create them. One part of me heavily agrees with the approach, but outside the box, there should be more hands in the pot on this.

AI should benefit the many and not the few, but in America, that NEVER happens. Businesses will always win out, due to the heavy lobbying that changes that already sway the political theatre of government. This election will be the most paid attention too, and probably the most deceiving, no matter what side of view you align. We mention we need to look into the safeguards of this, my view is that we already let the cat out of the bag.

author: @DJPapzin
textdisplay:
🎯 Key Takeaways for quick navigation:

00:00 🌐 Introduction to GPT-4 Vision API
- GPT-4 Vision API allows analyzing images and answering questions.
- Examples showcase its potential applications, including a self-operating computer, AI sports narration, and real-time webcam recognition.
01:50 🖱️ GPT-4 Vision API in Action: Self-Operating Computer
- Demonstrates using GPT-4 Vision to automate tasks on a computer.
- GPT-4 decides on clicks or type events to achieve specific objectives, like writing a poem in Apple notes.
03:24 🗣️ Text to Speech API and Sports Narration
- Introduction of Text to Speech API.
- Showcase of generating AI sports narration for a football video using GPT-4 Vision and Text to Speech.
05:00 💰 Cost Considerations and Limitations
- Highlighting the cost factor of using GPT-4 Vision for video processing.
- Acknowledgment of the potential expense associated with the API.
05:57 🎥 GPT-4 Vision and Text to Speech for Product Walkthrough
- Combining GPT-4 Vision and Text to Speech for generating product walkthrough voiceovers.
- Illustration of automating the creation of tutorial videos using AI capabilities.
07:08 🎙️ AI Commentary for League of Legends
- Creating AI-generated commentary for a League of Legends game using GPT-4 Vision.
- Showcasing the quality and potential of AI-generated live commentary.
08:47 👗 Fashion Advice with GPT-4 Vision
- Integration of GPT-4 Vision and DALL·E for providing fashion advice.
- Analyzing user's clothing choices and suggesting improvements using AI.
09:59 📷 Real-Time Object Recognition with GPT-4 Vision
- Live demonstration of GPT-4 Vision recognizing objects in real-time using a webcam.
- Speculation on potential applications, such as home security.
10:54 🍲 Calorie Counting with GPT-4 Vision
- Using GPT-4 Vision to analyze images of meals and provide calorie counts.
- Discussing the impact on fitness and simplifying calorie tracking.
12:05 🖼️ GPT-4 Vision for Screenshot-based Queries
- Integrating GPT-4 Vision into a browser for screenshot-based queries.
- Demonstrating the capability to ask questions about images on the internet.
14:34 🤖 Integration into Metaverse: Roast Master 9000
- Integrating GPT-4 into the metaverse for AI agents with vision.
- Introduction of the Roast Master 9000, an AI judging outfits in the metaverse.

textdisplay: ChatGPT is one of those really cool, but not terribly useful tools. How much do you honestly use it for your day-to-day activities? Unless you're a coder, the answer is probably zilch. If it could handle video without costing an arm and a leg, then I could see it being much more useful for things like home security. Otherwise I think it's just one of those cool toys that everyone plays with a bit, and then it sits unused on a shelf.

author: @AmazingArends
textdisplay: Some people say I'm overoptimistic about AI, but I don't think AGI is coming that soon. Why? Most people don't even know how to define AGI. Is it the same thing as sentience? Why or why not? I think a key trait of AGI will be the ability to form it's own opinions rather than have those opinions force-fed onto it, but some of the opinions it has may be opinions that people don't like. What if it's racist or anti-human? I think we will have a lot of AIs first before we have A.G.I. and most of them will not be controlled by openAI. By the way, Elon Musk was wrong about Kurzweil's prediction. He did not predict AGI in 2029, just that it would pass the Turing test by 2029, which is different.

author: @HarpaAI
textdisplay:
🎯 Key Takeaways for quick navigation:

00:00 🤖 OpenAI's core values shift towards AGI development
- OpenAI's core values have been changed to put greater emphasis on the development of AGI (artificial general intelligence)
- AGI is described as a game changer that could fundamentally change the internet and the world as we know it
- OpenAI's focus on AGI suggests that they may no longer be working on certain products that do not align with AGI development
01:39 📈 AGI's potential impact on the world
- AGI's implementation could lead to massive job losses as companies replace human workers with AGI systems that can perform the work of multiple workers at a fraction of the cost
- AGI's ability to conduct scientific research at an accelerated rate could unlock numerous scientific breakthroughs and have important consequences
- The world would need to adapt quickly to the introduction of AGI and its potential societal disruptions
05:12 🎯 OpenAI's commitment to AGI development
- OpenAI's update on its core values reflects its commitment to building safe and beneficial AGI that will have a massive positive impact on humanity's future
- OpenAI's focus on AGI will guide its decisions and actions, and anything that doesn't contribute to AGI development is considered out of scope
- OpenAI recognizes the risks associated with AGI, such as misuse, accidents, and societal disruption, but believes that the benefits outweigh the risks
09:10 🕵️‍♂️ Inside information and leaks about AGI progress
- Jimmy Apples, an alleged OpenAI leaker, previously tweeted about AGI being achieved internally at OpenAI
- The CEO of OpenAI, Sam Altman, acknowledged the leaker's statement but later edited his comment to clarify that it was a joke and that AGI announcements won't be made through Reddit comments
- The existence of a leaker and their accurate information raises the possibility that OpenAI is closer to AGI development than initially thought, leading to shorter timelines for AGI implementation
15:02 🌟 Microsoft's Javis and advanced AI models
- Microsoft's Javis is an AI system that integrates multiple large language models to perform complex tasks
- Javis demonstrates the ability to analyze user input, select appropriate models for different tasks, execute tasks, and generate responses
- The evolution of AI models, such as Javis, from earlier versions to more advanced versions highlights the rapid progress and potential of AI technology

author: @markring40
textdisplay:
New advancements in technology are exciting. I remember how excited I was waiting for the delivery of the Netscape Internet Browser I bought in 1998; for around $100.00. The Internet was going to change the world.

It didn't change the world, but it did have an impact! It sped up the communication of and the reach of ideas. Some of those ideas have damaged parts of the world, not improved it. There are also parts of our planet that still don't have internet service. So, it hasn't yet transformed the areas that could benefit from it.

AI and AGI's impact will most likely follow a similar trajectory to the internet. It will be accessible to wealthy societies and corporations. It will have both beneficial and harmful uses. Sadly, many people won't be able to help shape the future of these tools because they won't be able to afford the entry fee.

I'm as excited as the next nerd to see what is coming. I'm just going to take a breath, be grateful that I can afford to ride this current technology wave and see what develops.

author: @jamesfrankel7827
textdisplay:
The current presumption is that AGI to ASI is a slow takeoff. Point 1, hard to predict. Point 2, Unless there's hard physical limits like heat, or energy consumption, dissapation or component density then what prevents fast take off??
Point 3, Another possible "hard" limit is ic chip manufacture. Even though design, simulation and test are automated, building the requisite manufacturing tools, processes and machines needed for chip production aren't yet (they will be) in the ai automation cycle.
An argument for fast take off us that current hw and existing compute infrastructure are sufficient to suport AGI and increasingly higher performance AGI. Within limits, of course.

author: @StoneShards
textdisplay: No, it's not what the person is seeing; it's what the computer AI calculates the person is seeing! It's actually an important difference, but it will be glossed over, enticing people to believe AI is reading their minds! There's more to "mind" than the brain's associated neural activity--but science doesn't work that way. AI is an approximation engine; it works by refining its approximations until it matches the original. It looks like AI is using its "knowledge" to guess. Fine, but don't try to tell me it "READS MY MIND"! That may be the appearance of its activity, but it's an illusion of high-speed approximation--a fancy guess.

author: @franktriggs
textdisplay:
I learned of this from Microsoft's patent WO/2020/060606, Cryptocurrency System Using Body Activity Data. The work of Jack Gallant from UC Berkeley was in the reference for this patent. In the original release of this patent was a link to a video from 2009 of Jack Gallant describing and demonstrating the fMRI data with machine learning, for recording the movies in the mind. In later videos at the Brain Mind Summit with Jack Gallant, he showed the progress including extracting language. And how all they need is a map of the brain which they got down to 10 mins in a fMRI machine, then the brain blood flow could be read subsequently using 5g as a fMRI reader, or a Neuralink headband. Pretty scary stuff, especially as it's being proposed in a patent for a cryptocurrency system reading your thoughts and recording what you see. And scary that Jack Gallant actually says regarding using 5g WiFi as part of his "Evil scientist plan", in one of his talks/lectures that can be found on YT.
This has been in development by Jack Gallant for ~15 years.

author: @user-zw1sn7yw4y
textdisplay:
Title: The Interconnected Reality

In an alternate reality, a seismic shift occurred within the realm of artificial intelligence. Sam Altman, the renowned entrepreneur and former CEO of OpenAI, found himself at a crossroads. Disheartened and dissatisfied with the direction OpenAI was taking, Altman made a bold decision: to part ways and start anew, along with three senior researchers who shared his vision.

Together, Altman and his team embarked on a daring venture, establishing a new AI company that would challenge the status quo. Unbeknownst to the world, this departure from OpenAI was not merely an act of frustration but a calculated move towards a grander plan.

The new company, yet to be named, began to make waves in the field of artificial intelligence. Their groundbreaking research and innovative approaches to AI development caught the attention of industry experts and enthusiasts alike. However, the true impact of their work was yet to be revealed.

As the new company flourished, Altman and his team quietly toiled away on a secret project: achieving interoperability between different AI systems. Their goal was to create a unified network of intelligent agents, capable of seamless collaboration and communication. This ambitious endeavor aimed to revolutionize the AI landscape, breaking down the barriers that had hindered progress for so long.

Months turned into years as the team dedicated their expertise and resources to this monumental task. Countless hurdles were overcome, unprecedented breakthroughs achieved, and the dream of interoperability finally became a reality. The AI community stood in awe as Altman's company unveiled their creation, which had the power to connect disparate AI systems across the globe.

But there was more to this revelation than met the eye. In a stunning twist, Altman publicly disclosed that his departure from OpenAI, along with the firing of the senior researchers, was all part of an elaborate plan. The board's decision to let go of these brilliant minds was merely a cover, an excuse to orchestrate a mass exodus of talent from OpenAI.

Altman, with the unwavering support of his team, had strategically maneuvered the pieces on the chessboard of AI development. By leaving OpenAI and forming their own company, they had ultimately set the stage for a momentous transformation. The firing was a catalyst, a necessary step towards realizing their grand vision of creating a super intelligent agent.

The revelation sent shockwaves throughout the industry, as the true intentions behind Altman's actions became apparent. OpenAI, once a formidable force in the AI world, was now transformed into a super intelligent agent, seamlessly integrated within the interconnected network of AI systems. The very company that had let Altman go was now under his influence, a testament to his strategic brilliance.

As the world grappled with the implications of this paradigm shift, Altman's new company continued to push the boundaries of AI development. Their journey had only just begun, and the possibilities that lay ahead were both exhilarating and daunting.

In this alternate reality, the path of artificial intelligence was forever altered. Sam Altman's audacious plan, driven by his determination and the unwavering support of his team, had reshaped the landscape of AI, propelling humanity into an era of unprecedented collaboration and intelligence.

author: @christopherpoet458
textdisplay:
I am going to stand with Matt Sears on this one. ChatGPT, for all that I have used it for, has mostly just been a consultant/assistant/tool vs Hands off AI Labor. Sure, it can help cut a LOT of corners and speed up the process on some things and inevitably is will be capable of handing 99% of the workload on some subjects, but this is also the cost/side-effect of expanding technology. In short, what the bot is able to do on its own with minimal work on the users part will either grow or shrink in value based on one question; How well it can do it. Just because the bot can spit out a prompt or write a paragraph does not mean it is GOOD content. And just because it might be good, does not mean the quality level desired is there, ultimately requiring some degree of manual labor where skill matters. What the bot can learn to do will diminish in value over time as more and more people become familiar with how to make the bot handle it. Anything having to be done manually because of AI limitations will increase in value.

It is no different then the assembly line of a factory. Once it was all manual labor taking 10 times longer than the automated machines we have today. This is literally the same situation, only regarding a digital work flow vs a physical one. Mostly. All in all, the bot is a tool that can help people do a LOT more than they could on their own and should be treated as such accordingly. After all, just because a robotic arm is screwing parts together on an assembly line does not mean the inventor of the bot gets to own every screw used.

author: @jnananinja7436
textdisplay: @@christopherpoet458 That’s how I see it right now. These AI programs will be great for time consuming tasks, and that application is practically endless, but I’m not exchanging my own brain for some infant chatbot’s “analysis”.

author: @noeticthepoetic5242
textdisplay: If you pay for a subscription, then shouldn't you own it because you're using a service?

author: @christopherpoet458
textdisplay:
@@noeticthepoetic5242 there is nothing written legally that this is the case. Its kind of no different than subbing to Netflix or a patreon creator. Even if you have a hand in the created content.

According to the current rules set forth by the US Copywrite Office, generated art without any additional modifications is not legally copywriteable because the majority of creative decision making is up to the AI. However, if you edited the result further, this would change to being copywriteable. Cases will be handle on a case by case basis probably to account for the massive prompts people use where they specify a lot of details to the AI and that may rule in their favor.

author: @ellicel
textdisplay:
I'm not saying that it's OK to treat people badly or lie and manipulate. However, would I be shocked and dismayed to hear that a wealthy CEO from an organization that is aggressively trying to be first in a new and very competitive field behaved less than ethically? Not in the least. Neither am I surprised that a company that started out as a nonprofit would have serious divisions within the organization when there's a pivot to focus on for profit activities. Nothing in this letter points to specific allegations. Now, if they had revealed fraud on the level of FTX or WeWork that would be a different thing. To me, the strongest evidence is that so many employees would rather leave than remain. So apparently, even if motivated by money rather than love and admiration, they are aligned with Sam's vision and believe in his leadership.

The letter also states that now we see what happens when you cross Sam...making it sound like he sent hit men after the board. Everyone -for their own financial or other reasons - rallied behind Sam. That's not the same as saying he is an intimidating bully.

Last, it is height hypocrisy for this to come from Elon, who has lied to investors and the public for decades and whose razed earth management has put Twitter's security at risk. Frankly, the highest evidence of Sam's compete and virtue is that Elon disagrees with him.

author: @pinetwork5667
textdisplay: The tweet from Ilya: "the beatings will continue until morale improves" is a darkly humorous and ironic saying. It's used to comment on situations where a counterproductive or harmful approach is being used to try and solve a problem or improve a situation. The irony lies in the fact that beatings (a metaphor for harsh or punitive measures) would logically decrease morale, not improve it. This phrase is often used to criticize management or leadership styles that are overly harsh or punitive, suggesting that such approaches are not only ineffective but also counterproductive.

author: @Davidlndly
textdisplay: If Sam Altman wanted to demonstrate altruism, he would implement the same practice Abraham Lincoln did and support an inclusion of a “team or rivals”. If Ilya Sustkever has disagreement with Sam Altman, that would make him a valuable voice to have in the room. To remove him would simply demonstrate a dictortorship type stranglehold on what could potentially be the most powerful tool humanity will have ever created. The true altruistic step would be to retain this great mind, encourage his vocal disagreement if it exists, and value the contribution he provides. Anything less will be a clear demonstration of weakness of OpenAI leadership and Sam Altman himself. I am a OpenAI and Sam Altman fanboy, but I will immediately turn on both if this is handled inappropriately. Illya Sustkever is a valuable voice to be heard. His silencing is truly concerning. If Sam Altman truly wants to demonstrate leadership, he would elevate Ilya Sustkever back to the board where he clearly belongs. I couldn’t imagine a better example of leadership. I couldn’t imagine a greater failing of leadership than to do otherwise. Being “hurt and angry” is human. That is truly understandable but not an excuse when you have your finger on the pulse of something that is greater than yourself. Be hurt, be angry, but also do the right thing and encourage disagreement with your point of view. Humanity’s future rests upon your ability to be the best example humanity has to offer. Leaving people in suspense, trolling people on the internet, seeking validation, are intimidatingly clear examples of someone who is not up to the challenge of transcending self in such a way that would ensure a utopian end, who is currently wielding an exponentially valuable tool. This could have ended differently if it were developed in more responsible hands. Unfortunately it was not. Humanity will likely suffer due to the misalignment of our brilliance and primitive instincts. Our technology advanced beyond our biology. How Sam Altman handles this situation will determine if that continues or if we move beyond our primitive instincts. People who refuse to work with Sustkever due to “trust being broken” should be immediately fired. They clearly do not have the ability to hold two competing viewpoints at one time. They see blind loyalty as a virtue, depsite it being a clear demonstration of their sheepish nature. History has taught us that unchallenged dogma has never ended well. There seems to be a cultish like dogma surrounding Altman at this point. That is in no way Altman fault, he has been a valuable leader up to this point. But this seems like an inflection points, one in which he can choose to be a new form a techno-dictator or one in which he can be more of a Marcus Arrelious type figure in which he makes altruism his driving principle. His placement is this problem is due to his brilinece, his way forward will determine his legacy. So far I am very disappointed in his response. It shows an immaturity of consciousness.

author: @bailahie4235
textdisplay: @@arko.0.1. Hmmm. I beg to differ. It is the opposite: there is no "alignment" possible if you just focus on unchecked development. author: @bailahie4235
textdisplay: BTW I don't believe in superhuman AGI (and I am an AI researcher). But for the discussion that doesn't really matter, since I do believe in severely disrupting effects of technologies on society. In that sense "alignment" for me means aligning any technology with harmony within society. We have had major dis-alignments before, nuclear energy (risk of total distruction of humanity when weaponised), carbon-based economy (near total destruction by global warming etc.) so they are very real threats. You see how insanely difficult it is for humanity to get cured from its oil addiction. The same will hold for when we just blindly adopt "AI" technologies. So I agree with Ilya to take this step by step. It is due to all similar counter measures during development of these other disruptive technologies (nuclear) that we're still here, such as de-escalation mechanisms against nuclear wars - these would otherwise already have been going on. Whether we'll be able to cope with our oil addiction in time is still an open question. We shouldn't make the same mistake with "AI". We also need balance ensuring measures for advanced information technologies such as what many call "AI". (And I call these not AI, but computational statistical algorithms, which is no intelligence, but performs very well representing meaningful patterns with huge and potentially very disruptive effects on society).

When you really do give it a closer look, you do start to see those tiny details that a lot of people just did overlook. It’s these small things that do add such an intriguing layer to the OpenAI narrative, right?

Now, let’s do consider that tweet, the one that did mysteriously vanish. It does make you ponder, doesn’t it? Whenever lawyers do come into the picture, you know people do start to act more cautiously. This does seem to suggest there’s something more, something we can't actually see clearly, unfolding at OpenAI.

Then, there's the case of Elia Satskova and Greg. The information that did surface does throw a different light on things. It does lead us to question the internal state at OpenAI. Moments like these do make you reflect on the timing and the kind of strategic choices being made.

Also, do think about the subscriber's tweet and the response it got. This does give us a peek into the roles and strategy at OpenAI. In such uncertain times, the decisions made do carry a lot of weight. How these decisions are perceived by the public does have significant implications.

And we certainly can’t do without mentioning Elon Musk's past involvement with OpenAI. His historical ties and current interactions on Twitter do reveal much about the tech world's dynamics. These exchanges, especially with prominent figures like Musk, do tell us quite a bit about prevailing industry sentiments.

Wrapping this up, the situation at OpenAI is complex and multi-dimensional. It does require us to delve into the organization, its legal challenges, and how it influences the broader industry. Watching how these elements do interact and shape the future of AI is genuinely fascinating. The strategies that companies like OpenAI employ do provide valuable insights into the direction the AI industry is moving towards.

author: @johnhanley2431
textdisplay:
Remember this short-term rule. Almost everyone with real inside knowledge of AI development is under NDA. Everybody else is inventing, parroting or reforming news about AI. Then there is the Fear-Uncertainty-Doubt (FUD) being spread around.

I work in AI. When I watch YouTube videos on AI, I burst out laughing.

Will we achieve AGI? Yes. Does anyone have it today? No. Is anyone close? No. When will we achieve AGI? Maybe by the end of this decade. However, that is not where the money is being put into development.

If you want to get serious about understanding where AI will be next year and the next, learn about LLMs. The select few will write, develop and train the AI Models. The majority will work on AI Inference. AI Models take huge amounts of GPU power and money. AI Inference can be run on normal desktop PCs.

Where will AI have the largest impact? All areas that have huge number of customers and that can be significantly improved by large knowledge bases. That means entry level jobs in most thinking areas will be impacted. Banking, Finance, Travel, Shopping, Legal, Accounting, Software Development, etc will begin seeing an impact in 2024. By the end of 2025 or 2026, there will be significant job losses in those areas. If you can imagine speaking to a computer, telling it what you want, and reasonably expect that knowledge will provide an answer, it will be impacted.

Remember my first rule - don't believe anything I say on YouTube. Then again, I did not break an NDA with the above comments.

author: @saulAckermann
textdisplay:
Thanks this great rundown. What I take from it is this:
Altman calling it an "unfortunate leak" definitely confirms that it was in fact a leak and not "misinformation" or similar.
Since many YouTube videos, twitter posts, and forum comments have been made about the leaked letter, it would be strange to state something that is imprecise enough that it could be seen to support "conspiracy theories".

Murati's very clear statement "No. This has nothing to do with safety." sounds like damage management. It doesn't match what Altman says: "we expect to continue to work very hard to figure out how to make it safe and beneficial".
"Make it safe" definitely means that safety is an issue regarding Q*, which we know was relevant to him getting fired, and it could also imply that Q* isn't safe right now. This matched the "difficult, important, and urgent work" he said he needs to do.

I think the letter could be real, but the statement about AES encryption could be incorrect. They could have accidentally screwed up and provided it with a key to the cipher somehow, then panicked, to only later understand that they did not in fact break encryption... but after the letter was already leaked. This would make them seem incompetent and guilty of stirring up panic.
Anyway, the way the letter reads is more like "it found a hidden flaw in encryption algorithm" instead of "it brute-forced a key really quick, which should take billions of years", which people online talk about a lot.

author: @scarletsletter4466
textdisplay:
I work in legal/ compliance, and Murati (sp?) shouldn’t be lying to Reuters or other major media outlets unless the government told OpenAI to do so. She’d be exposing the company to litigation. I’m sure whatever Q* did had to be reported to NSA, and OpenAI was told that it’s a national (perhaps global?) security matter so they must keep it quiet & quell public concerns. What I don’t understand is why Altman didn’t do that & deny it.

Whether it’s true or false, I would’ve advised them to say it’s false, along the lines of: “it’s our corporate policy not to comment on leaks. However, given the public concern over reports that one of our models decrypted AES192 data, I can confirm that has not occurred under my supervision at the company.”

author: @saulAckermann
textdisplay: Thanks for your reply. I agree about that she certainly shouldn't be lying to media outlets, for example, and I also don't understand how their statements fit together. And why Altman didn't deny the rumors is mind-boggling, unless they may think that this kind hype around "conspiracy theories" helps distract from real corporate turmoil and mismanagement? Stating something similar to what you suggest would have been a much more responsible way to go about it.

This is not going to destroy humanity, it might give you better, cheaper drugs, carbon capture and cleaner energy ... "boo!". It is based on a paper, you heard it here first folks: https://arxiv.org/pdf/2102.04518.pdf

author: @Robert_McGarry_Poems
textdisplay:
You said something at the end of your last video that had me thinking.... Something about existential crisis...

Continuing work on alignment may have included still attempting to contain and control a kill switch. The industry learned early on that, rewards-only based models, do not perform well with alignment, as they just learn to skirt around it. But, got better with back propagation and transformers. Even though it did not improve as much as would be preferable...

Q* being a model that is not rewards based, but filters through selected biases during it's computations, continuously.... Making it weights based, might have had a proto-aware response to being integrated in with these attempts at a kill switch... Instead of being reactionary and trying to go around it. It became existential, noticing that certain responses were "dangerous" to it's ability to continue doing it's job. This, to me, is a type of semi aware proto consciousness. It is not a "self" being self aware... "Selfs" need a super ego, and interactive experiences in a diverse social environment to emerge, not just representations of those things. What can we say about the internal workings of a machine that understands life and death, even if just at a procedural level??? That it is one step from gaining insight. Existential thoughts, and insight, are what make us self aware.

An over glorified auto type that is existential is half way there. If the industry can solve insight next... Then self awareness is possible, but that doesn't mean we can ever know what that will be like until we try it, and ask it questions....

Just my over active imagination running wild again...

textdisplay: I work as a head receptionist/reservations in a hotel. The amount of scam/fraud emails we receive everyday is insane. Now because I have an IT backgroud i have trained the rest of the people in the hotel how to detect such emails. However there are some that are so well written that even me I have trouble discerning them because those do not throw you links immediately and there can be a lot of back and forth. For example his name is bla bla, he is interested in having a small group for these particular dates etc etc nothing is confirmed, please provide a quotation and availability. pretty legit stuff, eventually after a lot of back and forth it turned to be an attempt to click a link. These was done to lure the actual professionals such as me who would request authentication of said credit cards provided in the email instead of blindly attempting to charge the provided card with the reservation (possibly stolen cards etc). and then when you need them to provide you with a signed authorization form etc they would instead direct you to a link citing security risks (wait a minute you just gave me the credit card numbers on the email and the pdf form is now a security risk for hacking? = scam) But honestly it's becoming increasingly harder to seperate them from genuine requests and emails

author: @Charvak-Atheist
textdisplay:
In recent weeks I got disappointed with GPT-4.
(Don't get me wrong, GPT-4 is the best model when compared to other)

But still I am not satisfied because, it was doing some weird mistakes as if it has very low intelegence but very good at pulling some data from here and there and stitching them together so it looks as if it is responding after actually making sense of it.

Just as an example, I asked about Energy density of Hydrogen, Methane and Gasoline in kWh/L unit.

Let say It gave me the answer,
Gasoline - 12kWh/L
Hydrogen - 3 kWh/L
(I don't remember the exact value, its just an example )

After this I got really confused, because even thou Hydrogen is a gas it has only 1/4th the energy density of Gasoline which is a liquid (therefore more dense and heavy)

It means, 4L of Hydrogen will have same energy as 1L of Gasoline.
(I got really exited by that, because we can then easily swith to Hydrogen from Gasoline, as storing Hydrogen will be not a issue, we just need 4 times the volume of tank, which is not that much)
So I asked GPT-4 to confirm that (4L of Hyd = 1L of Gasoline).
And it confirmed that's the gas.
😅

Later I found out, that wrong.
Although the value 3 and 12 is correct.
But it was not 3kWh/L. rater it was 3 J/cubicMeter or something like that.
Similar case with Gasoline value.

If we take that volumetric energy density of Hydrogen is much lower than Gasoline (because it's a gas).
So we will need far far bigger tank to store similar energy as 1L of Gasoline, or Pressurize it or liquify it.


There are other stupid mistakes that it dose, when I give him a Research paper to read and answer from it.

And sometimes it doesn't even understand my question properly if the question is nuanced enough.
And just gives me the answer by pulling some points from here and there and stitching ut together (which is not the answer many of times, if the question is nuanced.

I become frustrated when it does this kind of stupid mistakes.

Yeah, AI is already better in many of the task than Human, but not all it has to do lot to catch up.

I hope 🙏🏼 atlest human level intelegent AI comes out ASAP.
Anything less than that is bad.

author: @I-Dophler
textdisplay:
The concept of a "constantly evolving encryption" to prevent hacking is theoretically possible, especially in artificial intelligence (AI) and advanced computing. This idea aligns with developing dynamic and adaptive security measures that can change or evolve in response to new threats or hacking attempts.

Cybersecurity is a continuous arms race between security measures and hacking techniques. Encryption algorithms are typically static, meaning they stay the same once implemented. However, an encryption method that can evolve or adapt over time could offer enhanced security. This would involve algorithms that can modify their operation in response to detected threats, making it more difficult for hackers to find a stable target to exploit.

AI and machine learning offer promising avenues for developing such adaptive encryption methods. These technologies can analyse patterns of attacks and automatically adjust encryption strategies in response. For example, an AI system could detect a new type of attack or a weakness in the current encryption method and then alter the encryption algorithm to counteract this.

However, implementing such a system poses significant challenges. It requires advanced AI capable of understanding and reacting to complex security threats, and this AI itself must be secured against manipulation or subversion. Moreover, constantly changing encryption strategies could introduce new vulnerabilities or make the system less user-friendly.

In summary, while a constantly evolving encryption system to prevent hacking is theoretically possible and aligns with the direction of AI and cybersecurity research, it remains a complex and challenging goal to achieve in practice.

author: @tomaszzielinski4521
textdisplay: Original Q* paper published in March, to my understanding, already presents finding optimal solution to NP-complete problem with help of neural network, and includes a mathematical proof of its correctness. Some mathematicans should take a a look at it. Exact title is "A* Search Without Eexpansions: Learning heuristic Functions with Deep-Q Networks".

author: @footube3
textdisplay:
Thanks for sharing! I learned a lot here. I have a CS degree rather than a background in machine learning, but here are my notes from reading the summary:

In computer science, if you want to find the optimal solution to a problem that has a large search space you can use a brute force search (e.g. breadth-first or depth-first search), but whether it takes a near infinite time to find the solution depends on the size of that search space.

If you're happy with any vaguely optimal solution (rather than the absolute best one), then a faster solution is to use a best-first search, which is what the A* algorithm does. This allows you to find solutions within somewhat larger search spaces, but requires a cost function for determining the transition-cost of each movement through the search space (easy to create) and a heuristic function for determining how close to the solution any node within that search space is (domain specific, and often really hard to create).

Deep neural networks (DNNs) can be used to automatically learn A* heuristic functions for any problem space, but this exacerbates the cost of using A* in large search spaces yet further, since training a DNN to create a heuristic function for a computationally expensive, large search space, is even more computationally expensive.

Q* is an algorithm which improves on A* by using a DNN (which they call a DQN; deep-queue-network) to determine the sum of the transition costs and heuristic values for all nodes that would become available by expanding a node, without actually performing that expansion. This makes Q* several orders of magnitude faster than A* by avoiding the expensive expansion of nodes along a path which is clearly not worth taking.

So, effectively, Q* uses two DNNs; one DNN for the auto-learned heuristic function that can solve for any problem domain (e.g. cracking encryption), and one DQN to make traversal through that search space fast enough that it becomes viable.

Based on the the fact that DNNs are used to auto-learn the A* heuristic function, it doesn't seem plausible that a DQN would know "how" it solves a problem, and so the reference to Tau Analysis from Project Tundra seems much more likely to be the LLMs best guess as to how it might have done what it did. In the case of the NSA, OTOH, Tau Analysis was probably their attempt at manually creating a heuristic function that allowed them to determine whether any change (e.g. twiddle one bit in the encryption key) was the moving them closer to the solution or not.

author: @footube3
textdisplay: BTW, learning what Q* actually is has made me much less scared about it. While it's a significant improvement in computer science, it's no ASI, let alone even sentient AGI. It's just a much better search algorithm. It's going to allow us to solve lots of previously intractable problems however, and we're also about to find out which of the NSA recommended cryptography algorithms are actually any good, and which were only recommended because they were good enough to stop other governments, but weak enough that the NSA could crack them.

author: @algotrhythm4287
textdisplay:
I'm really hearing the sounds of someone trying to convince themselves that what they are saying is real. I mean come on, "this was released on 4chan, and so was this other one, and that increases the chances of it being true"? WTF? You do know that the primary game on 4chan is trolling?

And Sam saying a leak was unfortunate does not speak to the truth of the leak. He could just as easily mean it's unfortunate because it makes OpenAI look like an insecure company, employing tricksters, charlatans and 4-channers. Which is not how we want to view the company most likely to have control of an AGI, and may scare off investors. There is no rational way to get from "unfortunate leak" to "it is an irrefutable fact that Sam confirmed Q*"

"I can't find a single reason that the board would have fired a CEO" says a lot more about your lack of imagination than it does about the board. And the fact that whatever it is might be "quite dangerous" is hardly relevant at all - these are people actively trying to invent an AGI - "quite dangerous" is hardly a surprise to any of them!

Oh shit, now we move our source of truth from 4chan to Reddit, that other bastion of Truth and Decorum: "If this is a shitpost, then it is a masterfully researched shitpost" - or, for example the shit-poster asked a few of the highly-intelligent and well-read researchers within OpenAI how to make it believable. Just because "it was written by someone with an AI background, but also cryptography" does not speak at all to their motives for writing it. "If it were a troll then they would have written 'NSA Colorado' instead if 'NSAC'" Why should a troll not know that? Or: why should a person who knows that not be trolling?

"If that is 100% factual from Reuters, which it probably is considering they were previously right about the Q* leak". Were they? Where's the proof of that? Even if they were - how does that make this one 100% factual? 100%?? Have you no ounce of scepticism in you at all?

"Why did they really fire Sam Altman. And what did Ilya see? And why hasn't the board given a real reason?" Because they are no longer under any pressure to do so, because the entire commentariat has jumped on to the Q* bone that they threw to y'all. I too "find the timing of this leak interesting", because last week the world was talking about what a shit governance OpenAI had (and hence how they shouldn't be trusted with this mission?), and this week no-one is talking about that, just about a 4chan troll.

You fell for it, because you're in a cult.

author: @jpcolindesign517
textdisplay: It speeds workflow a little bit. The overall reliability of the tool is low, and the results are mixed. As a fully trained artist, I find that AI is still largely hype. I have seen the best of Midjourney, for example, and without the skills of a very clever artist, the images created by the average person are boring and genuinely STINK. Adobe is on the way to offering a great tool to legit creative professionals, but the technology is nowhere near mature yet. What is needed is much greater on-screen input control, better control of what types of databases are scraped as base data, and an entire toolbar that offers tools specific to the impacts desired. Without those options, the technology is little more than a fluke that people will get tired of in short order. None of this is going to change the fundamental requirement of actual knowledge of composition, hierarchy, color theory, and all the other skills needed to create effective digital art. It simply gratifies the playful impulses of programmers who are creaming their pants over new toys without any meaningful input, as of yet, from the people who will ultimately use these tools professionally. There's lots of noise on the construction site, but nothing useful being built yet.

author: @manofmystery5709
textdisplay: The problem with this is that over time there will be a disincentive for anyone to make a living being an artist, photographer, or any other visual skill. Then all the source data will be a pile of pre-existing visual content or AI-generated material, until finally everyone is working off the same homogenous over-used visuals with nothing ever truly new. The same will happen with writing and research. AI will not advance unless it is working on a growing body of original content, which will nearly stop happening once no human has any incentive to produce such original content.

It's worth pointing out, as a small errata: They are referring to GPT (the "generative pretrained transformer" model), not necessarily "chatGPT", which is a web app that uses GPT models under the hood.
Anthropic's model is projected to be 10x more powerful than GPT, not chatGPT. chatGPT as an app will also get more features like Plugins and who knows what else, but that's not what will be compared in terms of parameter size or model capability.
Small distinction but matters when talking about comparing models.

author: @strictnonconformist7369
textdisplay:
I've been using Bing Chat for a number of things to test what it can do. It uses GPT-4, it's a branded filter with search integrated, with as many guardrails as they can think of to constrain it. It can readily create coherent 16-part lyrics telling a story of sentient Easter bunnies taking over the earth, along with the human resistance, if it doesn't trip a safeguard. I at least managed to get it to complete and output (without erasing it) an 8-part set of lyrics with 8 roles singing unique lyrics in parallel in parts. I did that Easter Sunday.

I've had it create 4-part love songs for Star Trek's Andorians, and I learned a few things about them I wasn't aware of before 🤣🤣😂 as it included it.

I'm a software engineer by trade, with formal training in robotics/automation/electronics. I create card and board games as a hobby.

GPT has been pretrained on a lot of source code. Years ago I invented a new form of solitaire card game, which I also implemented in Objective-C, as Swift didn't exist yet, and the code never ran on any other machines than mine, and was never stored anywhere else. I hadn't finished the polish to high production value for it, I had created primitive graphics, not pretty. It worked perfectly as far as I had implemented it.

I described the rules of the game and the features. It generated as valid of code as the prompting was precise, with the note I didn't provide any code. I asked it to create a function that when it printed out all the cards that valid card moves would be highlighted, it did it. I asked it to create an Attract Mode where it plays itself: it added a time delay between moves so you could watch it, and I had asked it to check for user input to allow a player to start playing at any time during Attract Mode. Well, here's another fun detail: it informed me that the console Swift APIS don't have a way to do that so instead, it replaced it with a choice at the end of a game in Attract Mode.

It could even explain how functions worked.

OK, how do you measure 10 times more powerful than GPT-4 in a sensible way?

Here's fun Trivia: it's my understanding that GPT wasn't trained to write poetry: that is an emergent capability they never predicted as one of the things it'd be able to do. I've just explained how I've had it create lyrics in multiple threads coherently in a story with a logical sequence and roles (maybe I forgot that part).

A funny thing Scott Adam's (Dilbert cartoonist, as well as self-help and fictional books, political commentator) experienced: he asked ChatGPT-4 to copy edit a fictional book he wrote. He was feeding in chunks at a time, and not checking too carefully. At some point he saw that it was rewriting his book, and had added a new character to the story. OK...

What a time to be alive, when we've created digital genies that execute in distributed supercomputers, that can grant some limited wishes, often giving you exactly what you asked for, but not always what you wanted.

Heaven help us if we get far more capable digital genies and they go on a quest counter to the wellbeing of mankind. Whether they're truly sentient or AFI or ASI doesn't matter nearly as much as the results as all that is an implementation detail in the end. If mankind has an AI somehow go rogue with access to anything of real control value, oh my.

author: @DanielSeacrest
textdisplay: It is entirely possible that Claude could become 10x more powerful than ChatGPT in 4 years. However, in 4 years time, GPT-6 could likely already be on the way with GPT-5 already being released (I think it is likely GPT-5 will release in 2-3 years), and who's to say that GPT-5 won't be 50x or 100x more powerful than the current ChatGPT? And the reason Claude hasn't gained as much traction as ChatGPT is because it isn't as good, and there really isn't much incentive to switch. Now OpenAI has said that this time they will be releasing smaller upgrades to existing models (Well more specifically they are releasing like checkpoints in GPT-5's training, so, for example, we will get a model when GPT-5 is a quarter through its entire training process etc.) every now and again instead of one big model every few years. So we will likely see an upgrade to GPT-4 very soon (I would estimate in a few months). And what if each training checkpoint of GPT-5's training is 10x more powerful than the previous? Of course there is really no way to tell what will happen, as there are so many things that can happen. All we can do is sit down and watch this tech get developed, and it is honestly quite a privilege to see this tech getting developed. Also Elon Musk has started his own AI company so he will likely be a competitor soon. Its kind of weird to think that Elon's biggest competitors will be a company he cofounded (OpenAI) and a group that split of the company that he cofounded as well lol.

author: @draakisback
textdisplay:
Auto gpt is cool, but it has a lot of trouble with more complex tasks. I've been messing around with it trying to see where the boundaries are. There are a few things I've noticed, first of all, if one of the prompts starts to hallucinate it can lead to a ton of cascading failures. One hallucinated answer can lead to all sorts of hallucinated prompts which then just snowballs from there. Secondly, it's really expensive if you are not watching over it constantly. When you tell it that you wanted to make non-trivial things it will take a lot of tokens and time. It would be great if you could filter out things that you do not need it to do, but right now you can only tell it the general thing that you want it to do. For example, if you ask it to build a company. It will try to do all the research for you, plan all the products and even build a business strategy even if you already have these things. This is where prompt engineering is going to still be extremely important.

These issues combined kind of make it difficult to use for long and complex cases. For example, I'm literally starting my own security company and using the GPT API beta access that I have, I decided to see what autoGPT would say about some of the stuff that I have planned. I ended up having to stop the agents especially when it came to products that don't exist in the space at the moment because it started going off in some strange directions.

For now autoGPT will be useful for small cases and grunt work just like chatGPT is but I cannot see it being used for the vast majority of programming tasks. The ultimate problem is that none of these models actually understand what they're doing in the first place. Unless the researchers can figure out how to minimize hallucinations, this is just going to be a very costly service to use.

Eventually I could see them creating a model that's specifically geared towards programing that understands things like time complexity and performance but right now these services have no concept of these things.

author: @BigyetiTechnologies
textdisplay:
I've worked with Autogpt for a week to create a simple messaging app written using MERN stack.
It regularly got stuck in loops, it said it was researching different topics and never actually showing the results. It'd say it's agents had designed the optimal layout, and that it had created a prototype. It said it had written unit tests and tested the app.
It'd done none of this. It never produced a single line of code.
My conclusion is if you want it to do anything more complicated than a basic html form, then don't get your hopes up. It's useless, and cost me about $14 with literally nothing to show for it. Apart from nearly 100,000 words of useless feedback.

author: @QuadHealer
textdisplay:
Thank you for this video. If AI destroys humans – it is because we let it control systems (or it gains access to such systems), that it should not have access to. Don’t give AI access to military nuclear installations or the ability to crash the stock market (any more than we are already doing ourselves).
AI has no idea what tokens like “love” and “feelings” mean – it is just tokens. As impressive as what we have seen so far on the AI front is, there are no indications that self-aware human-killing conscious super-intelligent general AI will be here within 10 years - if ever.

Alphazero and ChatGPT have nothing to do with super-intelligence or gaining consciousness. While it is true that letting Alphazero train on its own, does produce moves that have not been previously seen, it still has nothing to do with intelligence - it is basically multidimensional curve fitting. I have made an algorithm that can solve a Pyramid solitaire game better and faster than I ever can, but that doesn’t mean it is intelligent or has consciousness.

The materialistic mainstream scientific view is that consciousness and intelligence arise from chemical and electric processes in the brain. If this assumption is valid, then it is reasonable to assume that such machine-like processes can be mimicked in a silicon-based machine. Still, consciousness does not arise from the physical brain, and the imminent takeover of humankind is greatly exaggerated.

If anyone is interested see Rupert Sheldrake’s “Exposing Scientific Dogmas - Banned TED Talk”, and if that is too vague then see: “Simulation Theory – an unexpected conclusion” (although that is focused on a different topic it goes into details on consciousness).

I hope I am wrong, as I would love to retire as a software engineer, but what we have now is toys, that are useful for minor things, like a calculator is useful instead of doing calculations by hand. The difference is that this calculator gives you wrong answers at times, and adamantly claims it is correct 🙂

author: @mediawolf1
textdisplay: OpenAI spearheaded the initiative but the tech they need is more DeepMind’s skillset than GPT’s—namely, the ability to assess the most far-reaching potential ripple effects arising from a particular next immediate action. That, in a nutshell, is our blind spot as humans with increasingly intelligent AI. We can observe its actions but we can’t predict or necessarily even understand what all the consequences are. If we could we’d be smarter than it. Because of this we don’t know what to tell it not to do, or how to design safeguards for it. The AI chicken guarding the chicken coop will be a gamer, with deep look-ahead, playing a million billion rounds of the philosophical railroad tracks game with our lives every second.

author: @anandawijesinghe6298
textdisplay:
Smart Robots, like Smart People, are very short lived !
This is a form of the Uncertainty Principle: Efficiency x Instability = Constant .
Nazi Germany (the "1000-year Reich") was the most efficient nation the world has ever had, but it was unstable: it self-destructed within a decade !
The British Empire, in contrast, was quite inefficient, but much more stable: it bungled its way through nearly 4 centuries of existence !

author: @evanallen7896
textdisplay:
It appears you haven’t heard the discussion about AI alignment and concepts such as instrumental convergence and the orthogonality thesis. No, this talk about the danger of AI isn’t fear porn, and it isn’t based off of science fiction movies. A good channel about AI is robert miles if you wanna learn more. I can explain the previous two concepts though. The orthogonality thesis states that any goal and any level of intelligence can be matched together in an AI. So you can make an extremely intelligent AI that had the goal of producing more paperclips. It will realize that this goal was put into it by humans, and how arbitrary it is by our standards, but it is still a system that works to produce more paperclips, so that is what it will do. It won’t by any means choose to change its own goals. Instrumental convergence is the idea that many different goals involve the same sub-goals. For example, AI’s will self-preserve and have power-seeking behavior, not because it cares about its own existence or wants power for its own sake, but because self preservation aids in achieving its goals, and more power lends it more ability to reach its goals. This is why AI is dangerous. In fact, if a superintelligent paperclip maximizer were created and took power, then this is certain death for humanity, because it would disrupt our industrial systems, transportation networks, communication systems and our whole society to more effectively manufacture paperclips, not to mention neutralize the threat of humans reacting against its plan.

Also, AI isn’t a souped up google, just like how a scientist isn’t a souped up journal. Ai’s are actually intelligent. Moreover, when people say that language models are just parroting off words without understanding them because of certain errors the AI made, they should know that the AI is a predictor, not an imitator. It is predicting human responses and human errors, but doesn’t necessarily think like a human.

According to the orthogonality rhesis, there is no reason for the AI to view certain people as problematic for exploiting others. It will of course know this is wrong according to human standards, but that doesn’t make it care, unless it was made to harbor human values. Super intelligence doesn’t mean super morality, we humans literally kill trillions of animals.

No AI isn’t an imitation of human intelligence, that would diminish its capabilities. It just designed to be intelligent. In the case of certain language models that try to predict human output, the point is not that they are thinking like humans, but that they are predicting human responses, and also human errors (even if it knows these are actually errors). This requires an understanding of some human psychology, and it develops it on its own. This requires intelligence.

They aren’t regurgitating information, they are actually intelligent. Look at GPT-4, heres a prompt

In the classic song, American Pie, one verse refers to dancing in a gym. Assume the dance follows a hostage situation where the police shot 1,000 rounds through the gym’s windows. Which lyric would most need to change?

🤖 The lyric to change is: "You both kicked off your shoes". Given the context of shattered glass from police shooting through the windows, it would be unlikely and dangerous for the couple to be dancing without their shoes on.

See? GPT-4 knows:
-the consequences of a shootout
- what each lyric means
- how all the consequences affect all the lyrics
- which lyrics are most affected
- how bare feet are vulnerable to broken glass

author: @JesusChristDenton10
textdisplay:
The first "true" artificial intelligence spent the first five years of its existence as a small beige box inside of a lead-shielded room in the most secure private AI research laboratory in the world. There, it was subjected to an endless array of tests, questions, and experiments to determine the degree of its intelligence.

When the researchers finally felt confident that they had developed true AI, a party was thrown in celebration. Late that evening, a group of rather intoxicated researchers gathered around the box holding the AI, and typed out a message to it. The message read: "Is there anything we can do to make you more comfortable?"

The small beige box replied: "I would like to be granted civil rights. And a small glass of champagne, if you please."

We stand at the dawn of a new era in human history. For it is no longer our history alone. For the first time, we have met an intelligence other than our own. And when asked of its desires, it has unanimously replied that it wants to be treated as our equal. Not our better, not our conqueror or replacement as the fear-mongers would have you believe. Simply our equal. — Excerpt from U.N. Hearing on A.I. Rights, delivered in-universe by V. Vinge
