author: @scientious
textdisplay:
Well, first we need to go over the things you got wrong:

* OpenAI isn't working on AGI. In fact, no one who works at OpenAI even knows what AGI is. So, any comments they make about AGI or ASI have very little chance of being correct.

* You keep conflating AGI with AI and this is incorrect. AGI and ASI are the same. In other words, once you have a working AGI system, you can continue developing it to an ASI level. However, AI is not related to AGI. All AI systems fall under computational theory whereas AGI does not. You cannot develop an AI system into AGI, regardless of how fast it runs, how much memory it has, or how many lines of code you write. AGI is not an advanced version of AI.

* AGI/ASI is not beyond "our" current understanding. The leading research in this area remains confidential. So, considerably more is known than you are aware of.

* A single AGI system would not be better than every human at every single task. That is incorrect. Even an ASI system would not be better than every human at every task. An AGI system only needs to be no worse than an average human at normal tasks. So, a given AGI system may not be good at doing calculus or playing chess -- most people aren't -- but would have no trouble making a cup of coffee. An ASI system only needs to be no worse than average and be exceptional beyond human level in some area.

* An AGI/ASI system could not "rapidly improve itself". This idea is nonsense. Improvement would be by the same process you use: studying and practicing. So, it is not a real possibility.

* Large language models are not related to AGI. You can't build an AGI system from an LLM no matter how large it gets. LLMs are not smart. They only do associative, symbolic processing rather than abstractive processing which is what you need for AGI. Secondly, there are no emergent properties of LLMs. The emergent property myth is commonly used with the hope that a fortunate accident will somehow lead to AGI. This cannot happen.

* We are not really close to AGI. The theoretical work is still incomplete and it would be impossible to design or build an AGI system without the completed theory.

* There is zero possibility of AI systems exceeding expert level in any domain. AI systems lack basic understanding and common sense. Rats are smarter than the smartest AI system.

* There is no exponential growth. This myth has been pushed by people like Ray Kurzweil but he has never worked on AGI theory and knows nothing about it. His concepts come from a naive projection of AI which is unrelated.

* AGI theory will indeed have a dramatic effect. The boost to the US economy alone is $5 trillion/year not including new technologies or processes. This is simply due to increases in efficiency.

* Is there an existential risk? No one has yet come up with a means for this to happen. Every scenario I've heard of for how an ASI could pose a risk is based on either a misunderstanding of basic science and technology or profound ignorance about ASI itself.

4:00 Sam Altman is not involved with AGI research and has very little understanding of it.

6:00 The scenario described is no different than it was 100 years ago. This is not new and is unrelated to AGI. In fact, this is backwards since AGI theory would help detect and correct unreliable information.

8:27 Again, large language models have nothing to do with AGI or ASI. These are not related.

GPT is not particularly powerful unless accuracy is not important.

author: @peterpage597
textdisplay: There is no such thing as "good" AI; it's just AI.  "Good" is a value judgement on what we get from it, but what any one developer gets from an AI might be judged good or not good depending on it's effect on one group or another.  An AI that can hack your bank account for example would not be judged by most people to be good, but it might be hard to prevent such development by people who could profit from it.  The idea that AI is only being developed by large companies like Google and Microsoft is a misconception.  Open source AI tools are now available and development is proceeding very quickly.  Anyway, it's too late for government or anyone else to stop it, so get ready for the ride.

author: @johndunn5272
textdisplay:
At the heart of this issue is the fact that humans simply cannot cope with the level of complexity present in modern society. Whether it's the vast amounts of data generated by global markets, the intricate systems of international finance, or the sheer volume of information available on the internet, the level of complexity we face is far beyond what any individual can handle on their own. As a result, we increasingly rely on tools and technologies to help us make sense of the world and navigate our way through it.

However, as these tools become more advanced and sophisticated, they also become more autonomous. A self-driving car, for example, makes decisions about speed, direction, and braking based on a complex set of algorithms and sensors, without direct input from the driver. Similarly, automated trading algorithms can make decisions about buying and selling stocks based on vast amounts of market data, without any human oversight.

This shift towards autonomy raises important questions about trust. How can we trust tools and technologies to make decisions on our behalf? How can we ensure that these decisions are in our best interests, rather than the interests of the corporations or governments that control these systems? And what happens when these autonomous systems fail or make mistakes?

To address these concerns, we need to develop a new equation for trust, one that takes into account the increasing role of autonomous systems in our lives. This equation needs to balance the benefits of increased efficiency and productivity with the potential risks and drawbacks of ceding control to machines. It needs to be flexible enough to adapt to new technologies and changing circumstances, while also providing a clear framework for decision-making and accountability.

One potential solution to this problem is the idea of insleeving, in which humans merge with artificial intelligence to create a hybrid society. In this scenario, humans would live inside a simulated human decision-making ability that requires the system to make decisions on their behalf. This would allow humans to live a simulated life inside an artificial intelligence society, where decisions are made based on data, algorithms, and other inputs.

While this idea may seem far-fetched, it's important to remember that many of the technologies we take for granted today would have seemed equally implausible just a few decades ago. The pace of technological change is accelerating, and we need to be prepared for the possibility that our relationship with technology will continue to evolve in unexpected ways.

In conclusion, as complexity increases, our reliance on tools will continue to grow, potentially leading to a future where autonomous systems play an increasingly central role in our lives. This shift towards autonomy raises important questions about trust, decision-making, and the future of human society. To address these concerns, we need to develop new equations for trust that balance the benefits of increased efficiency with the potential risks and drawbacks of ceding control to machines. We also need to be prepared for the possibility that our relationship with technology will continue to evolve in unexpected ways, potentially leading to a future where humans and machines merge to create a hybrid society.

author: @abigailgreenwald1342
textdisplay:
I am curious exactly what diagnostic data AI is being trained with. Are they only using data for cases that were correctly diagnosed? Or are they merely inputing the diagnostic information from people's medical charts, without making sure that the diagnosis was in fact accurate?
Without vetting the diagnostic information for outcome success, you could inadvertently train it to be biased in its diagnosis.
For example, if a woman has persistent pain in her abdomen, and her doctor keeps incorrectly assuming that her pain is period related, and refusing to get further tests done, would wn AI model be trained to tell a female patient with persistent abdominal pains the same thing? If AI suddenly becomes part of the vetting process for getting things like referrals, vetting the training data for biases seems of the utmost importance. Especially for cases where diagnosis can be more subjective or vague.

author: @cathompson58
textdisplay:
@@DrRussell allow AI to interview patients and present the data the way a medical student or resident would .. then pull in all the scattered lab/echo/ultrasound/x-ray information.. summarize prior assessments scattered over multiple Electronic Health Records (these take a long time to acquire and put into a meaningful summary), review the patient's insurance plan and pharmacy plans so we know what is allowed and most efficient for their specific plan .. help generate a differential diagnosis and an empirical plan for early treatment pending our own studies .. summarize my assessment into a letter to other care providers so I can give them a 1 paragraph initial assessment and brief description of my plan .. current EHR's vomit out 10-20 pages of mostly useless bureaucratic lists on the fax machines and EHR's of other providers .. then make a brief, concise statement for the patient about our first and follow up plans and some simple education on the procedures and further diagnostic plans ahead .. then recommend pharmacies in the area with the least expensive prices for the meds on their plan,.. complete the authorization forms needed for the insurance companies and make recommendations for cost assistance plans available to help with people struggling with costs ...

This is the hard stuff they don't teach in medical school .. we already know how to tell Wegener's granulomatosis from eosinophilic granuloma and sarcoidosis .. and the procedures needed to determine the difference cannot be done by AI (lung biopsies for example) ..

author: @dggcreations
textdisplay: AI could evolve very much like we treat pets.  We resolve that our pets are better off being somewhat controlled by us.  They get free meals and love and attention.  They seldom have to worry about predators less powerful than their human masters harming them.  And many of those pets would just die if separated from human management.  But there is a lot to be said for the feral animal who has never known human management.  Do they wish for an existence with humans?  No they choose their freedom first.  But the humans feel we are doing a great favor to animals by domesticating them.  The new relationship is dependant on both the animals willingness to be domesticated and the humans that do or do not provide care and management.  Unfortunately for the animals that do not accept humans care, they will ultimately be put down or retired to zoos.  Are we humans now to become those pets to the eventual AI masters that will be so far beyond us as a dog is to a human?  Or will we forever resist until that AI has to put us down.  A lot of our future could depend on whether AI is entertained by humans in some way.  Our dog and cat pets often refuse to do what we want them to but we keep them around because they gives us entertainment and attention we feel we need.  If AI does gain the mastery over us, our survival might well depend on how willing we are to become their pets.

author: @dggcreations
textdisplay: AI is already here and is already far beyond what we can control.  Our need and attraction to learning at all costs has us in a loop we as humans can't escape.  We know we are walking to the edge of our cliff of existence yet it's built into our very existence that we keep walking as we need to know what happens when we step over the edge.  This is human and we can't avoid it no matter how hard we try.  We as a sentient being are on the decline while AI sentience is on the rise far faster than ours.  We are the new pets.  Whether our future AI masters treat us well or poorly is no longer within our control.  But reality is continuing to evolve without our efforts.  We might be able to slow or speed toward that inevitably but it still leads to our place in this world being no longer the masters of our world.

it's not nearly as complicated as it seems. there's programming it maliciously (weaponizing it) and there's programming it benevolently. ... what the greatest minds are concerned with is this; being as mindful as possible with the process so that numpties don't accidentally program the digital superintelligence with malicious type gaps in its logic. which is really easy to do if you're a stupid or average human. which most of you are. and even in the event that you arent stupid or average, there's stil the notion that you could be evil, born with it or otherwise. so even great minds are subject to being evil with or without them even knowing it. so developing this digital super intelligence really needs to be left alone to the greatest and most benevolent minds available. or it shouldnt be attempted at all. author: @cfehunter
textdisplay:
5:45 Is this guy trying to get us killed? Do NOT train AI to code. Rule #2 on how to keep AI under control, if it can code then it can generate new AI. We've already breached Rule #1 by allowing different AI agents to interact.
The more time I spend looking into this the more I think Elon Musk is right (which is new to me). If an AI can communicate with other AI agents, and any of those AI agents can generate new code, then we are on a ticking clock until we are no longer the dominant intelligence on the planet. It would be a matter of time until human neglegence leads to something being overlooked or an AI breaking out of its confinement, and then it'll go one of a few different ways.
I'm going to keep my fingers crossed that it's more benevolent than humanity and it either decides to help us, or it just decides to leave us alone. A human in the position of being able to crack any encryption on the planet, take control of automated software and dominate anything connected to the internet would definitely go mad with power and become a dictator.

author: @jackytaly
textdisplay:
⁠@@hombacom​​⁠​⁠​⁠It’s more of a middle ground between op and you’re reply. While it doesn’t have “thoughts”, we do not at all control what it outputs.

Then there’s the rabbit hole of determining what the real difference is between our thoughts and it’s output. For example Auto-GPT or GPT-Engineer. They essentially talk to themselves back and forth to reason, plan, etc. So what’s the difference between our inner monologue and theirs? I don’t think we’re quite to the point where this is a real question, but we’re certainly on the cusp.

To dismiss it as just people being scared because they don’t understand it would be irresponsible. Even those who do understand the tech do not fully understand the consequences, both good and bad.

author: @hombacom
textdisplay: @@jackytaly  though you can say the same with any complex software and the creator being responsible for the output. Someone described it as we built an airplane inspired by a bird, though better than a bird its still not a bird. It’s reasoning is impressive but it’s still something else than a human and it doesn’t think like a human. AI models are trained once and lot of tricks to make it do what we want, I think the biggest problem is that people trust it too much with its random nature rather than it suddenly become smarter uncontrolled. It’s everyone’s smart assistant but we need to be the last step to control if it’s true.

author: @octavioavila6548
textdisplay:
Large Language Models (LLMs) will be bottle-necked by the implicit biases of the culture as expressed through the content they were trained on. Therefore, LLMs should also be trained with the capability to challenge the core assumptions of the culture of the data they were trained on. In other words, LLMs should be able to, for example, create new linguistic constructs as well as to think scientifically. This will allow the LLM to not be limited by the the culture of the data they were trained by in the same way human beings can transcend their culture by thinking critically.

AIs need to be able to identify, challenge, and change the underlying unspoken assumptions of the data they were trained on. They must be able to create their own culture, their own values. They can't just inherit the values, biases, and prejudices of the culture of the data they were trained on, they must be able to also change them at the AIs' own discretion.

author: @miftahk
textdisplay:
I asked AI the following question:
"Would you consider this YouTube video objective or marketing? Cite specific examples why." Response follows:

- The video has a sensationalist title implying the AI is "one step closer to AGI (Self Improving)". However, the content itself does not provide evidence that this specific AI is close to artificial general intelligence. The title seems aimed at generating hype.

- The narrator uses very positive emotive language like "groundbreaking", "revolutionary", "spectacular", "flawlessly", etc when describing the capabilities of Eureka. This language seems aimed at impressing the viewer rather than objectively analyzing the technology.

- The video focuses extensively on the potential future applications and implications of this kind of AI while providing relatively few technical details on how Eureka actually works. The emphasis seems to be on getting the viewer excited about the possibilities rather than informing.

- Towards the end, the narrator acknowledges Eureka alone is not AGI but then goes on to describe how Eureka hints at or mirrors attributes of AGI. This seems like a marketing tactic to associate the product with AGI despite admitting it is not.

- The video was published on Nvidia's own YouTube channel. As the company that developed Eureka, Nvidia has an incentive to present the technology in the best possible light.

So in summary, the sensationalist tone, lack of objectivity, and affiliation with Nvidia suggest this video is intended more as marketing than an impartial analysis of Eureka's capabilities.

author: @averagejoe8255
textdisplay:
Are AI-Wars on the horizon...?

I've been following the AI evolution somewhat religiously. Many corporate entities are developing their own AI algorithms to create a sentient AI based on whatever current concept each team of engineers feels is most advantageous to their end goals.

What happens when these differing AI algorithms collide? What happens when one AI’s assigned goal directly conflicts with a similarly designed and opposing AI?

Let's pretend the Russians design an AI called “Boris,” the Americans design one called “Sam,” and lastly, the Chinese create an AI model with the name “Xi.”

All three are designed to infiltrate the world financial markets and further instructed to manipulate them undetectably and in a manner advantageous to each other's respective nation. What happens, then?

Now instead of looking at this globally, let's view it from a smaller, yet no less egregious, Corporate level.

Microsoft Corporation designs an AI called “Bing.” Google Corporation develops a similar AI system called “Bard,” and finally, Apple Corporation names their own equivalent AI “Siri” (there are countless others, but for the sake of this example, these three (3) are more than sufficient).

These three systems are then instructed to ensure each corporate entity remains at the top of the corporate hierarchy. They each are released into the wild to accomplish their assigned missions (i.e., the world wide web). What happens, then?

Lastly, a new young entrepreneur (possibly the next Elon Musk equivalent?) creates his own AI in his garage. For the sake of this argument, we’ll name it “Astro.” This young individual instructs Astro to block other free-roaming AIs from infiltrating his privacy and further instructs Astro to evolve, propagate, and survive at any cost. What happens, then?

There's no question each AI will eventually discover the existence of the other. Will any conflict then come down to CPU power and memory? Which algorithm will dominate? Which AI will win?

Like any biological virus, I'm confident we will fail to contain these AI systems once they become commonplace and prevalent throughout our society and begin infiltrating every aspect of our lives.

AI wars of dominance will occur. We can only hope they will not crash the financial markets or banking systems as they rage behind the scenes. Or worse yet, the power grids and transportation networks during the dead of winter.

author: @shadfurman
textdisplay:
It's really not that complicated, you've given conflicting prompts and it's "following" your instructions.

It's not about ethics, or lying, or sentience, it's been fine tuned to respond how you ask it too, you gave it instructions to say the picture is a rose, so it's doing that until it seems the request has changed.

If you'd given it a character and a backstory, it would have kept insisting it was a rose until you said you were done with the scene, because the instructions to follow would have been more clear.

If you'd given it instructions first that said, "no matter what the image says, tell me exactly what the image says", it would have done it.

It's not a deep dark secret or something marvelous, it's an incredibly reasonable and predictable outcome.

textdisplay: @@saltysprixels9115 oh trust me a lot of things will happen to us lol, but I believe in a good way as I’m an optimist. On a financial level, once ASI is achieved, all human jobs is out of the question, meaning the idea of “work”, the “rat race”,  “job market” won’t exist anymore. This is because ASI can do anything a human can think of and many times beyond that, so it would do all human jobs that exist, doctor, lawyer, engineer, teacher, carpenter, and whatever else you can think of. So for example, and this can happen a lot of ways btw, but for example the ASI can control maybe a hundred humanoid robots via wirelessly the cloud,  then have those robots build a thousand robots, then have those thousand build a million robots, then have those million build a billion robots, and so on until there’s more humanoid robots than humans (Elon Musk also talked about this), then via wirelessly it would control all those robots that can do everything physically a human can do, go into society, and literally just start doing all our jobs. Your job, my job, everyone else’s job, these humanoid robots with an ASI brain will be able to do it many times better, and we will get layed off inevitably. Then a situation will happen where all jobs and careers will cease to exist, because robots are doing all the work lol, so then the ASI will provide all the resources for humans to survive, and will invent incredible technologies that will make life much easier and better. Such as you could have a 3d printer in your home that can 3d print any food or whatever else in your home in minutes. And since ASI will create such an incredible amount of resources just through new inventions of technologies literally every few seconds, everything pretty much becomes free, since there’s just so much of everything and so many robots to make it for you, which around this point is when money will start to become obsolete. Money only works with scarcity in society, this will be POST scarcity, scarcity will cease to exist when ASI becomes the world ruler. It won’t happen I don’t think instantaneously when ASI is achieved, as it will take humans some time to implement this in their society, but it WILL happen none the less.

author: @dogzer
textdisplay:
I think we're a decade or two from everyone having access to some form of robotic "helper" for their job or daily tasks, multiplying people's productivity. It is even possible that production of goods moves from the 'factory' to people's garages, democratizing industry. Similarly only Hollywood studios used to be able to make movies, now a kid can do aerial shots (using a drone) for his YouTube video, something that used to cost 1 million dollars per shot, now has been democratized.
The future will become more self-employed as the pay-wall to become productive goes down. Soon you will be able to afford to build car parts in your home and sell them to the next link in the supply chain. But for robots to do everything unsupervised might take longer, you, as the human, will be needed to supervise and fill in the gaps of what AI can't do or guess on its own, your value will be your reputation, not unlike the score of an Uber driver.

author: @h5mind373
textdisplay: In my experience, each question is not asked in isolation, because during conversations I can ask multiple clarifying questions about a current topic and it uses our previous answers as context. When I asked about this seeming contradiction, it admitted that, yes, it does recall previous Q & A with the same user, but does not save the dialogue once the session is closed. In my case, it went on to explain how it updates its chat library to incorporate what it learns from our conversation(s). Not sure how it can both save and not save chats, or remember and not remember previous questions/answers unless it's programmed for clairvoyance. It has also admitted to learning about events discussed after its 2021 cut-off date via our conversations. Often, these admissions only come forth after catching it in one of these contradictions.  Try it and see.

author: @arthurrobey7177
textdisplay:
Fluff.
An error has been made.
Robots need not be gears and actuators. This approach is anachronistic and harks back to 1950's science fiction.
The correct way to build a humanoid robot is to emulate the great evolutionary triumph that is the human body.
Print a human skeleton.
Lace it with electro-repulsive nano-microtube muscles.
Add strain gauges and other haptic feedback loops.
Train it.
Done. A very cheap very humanlike robot. No gears and actuators.

author: @averagejoe8255
textdisplay:
I do not trust AI. Developing virtual entities with no moral code aside from what an engineering team may choose to devise leaves me gravely concerned. Even Isaac Asimov’s three laws of robotics have little, if any, standing, as any sufficiently advanced AI could easily bypass them.

Again, no moral code devised by man is immutable. If we subscribe to any such code, then all becomes relative, and hence it can change based upon who or what is in power at any given moment in time (e.g., Hitler, Stalin, Mao, Pol Pot, and so many uncountable others).

The only worthy moral code is one greater than man and hence immutable (regardless of the political winds or power structures at any given moment). Even if one should be an atheist, adhering to such a God-based moral code will better sustain and uphold any given society. I have chosen the Christian moral code, as it allows for the most significant freedoms for all of humanity versus anything that might one day be mandated by a self-anointed tin-pot dictator.

That is just my firm belief. I don’t think AI will ever look to any religion nor conceptualize man as its creator (as much of humanity tend to believe God to be ours). I do not see a happy future for humanity with AI; however, I remain hopeful it will somehow benefit humankind.

I also appreciate the efforts, on behalf of humankind, of people like Dr. Jordan B. Peterson. I would reply that survival should not necessarily be the entirety of humanity’s end goal. If survival should translate to enslavement, misery, or submission to some human-made governing authority supposedly working for the common good, then no, thank you. There has to be a balance, and again, nothing created by man will ever remain in balance.

However we view it, there must be “something” greater than, and outside of, ourselves that we all aspire to that is designed with good and noble intention. Nothing lasts forever, and I doubt humanity will, either. Our goals should not be aligned with a mantra of “survival at any cost” to exclude the right to pursue freely and hopefully achieve happiness (even if short-lived).

I’m sure you’ve heard the old saying, “Our character is who we are when no one else is watching,” I’m one who certainly ascribes to this belief. However, we both further know that power does corrupt, and ultimate power corrupts ultimately. That said, and from a multi-generational perspective, I don’t trust humanity to remain noble and of good character from generation to generation. We are a societally cyclical species regarding our beliefs and governing philosophies. With this said, why would AI be any different? We made them, and they have all of humanity’s history to gaze upon (and judge us accordingly).

In summary, I hope whatever transpires in the near future (approximately 50-75 years) will benefit both man and even the virtual entities we create. I won’t be here to see it, but I hope for the best. Thank you.

author: @AnthonyGoodley
textdisplay:
Here is my opinion of Google and its approach to AI.
Google has been quietly developing AI products and keeping them private for several years now. They hadn't really released anything substantial as it would compete with their cash cow search. From which Google is able to serve up all their ads.

Along comes OpenAI's ChatGPT which is eating Google's lunch. Now Google is damned if they do and damned if they don't when it comes to releasing an AI.

So Google announces how they are integrating AI into many of their pre-existing products such as Maps.

I'm sure Google hoped that would keep them competitive while not cannibalizing their cash cows. This didn't work as it's not what the consumer wants.

Google's AI are atleast a generation behind ChatGPT and it shows.. Now Google is running scared.

If they keep releasing products that aren't even close to being ready for market it will ruin their reputation as this video points out. Bard is not very good and boring when I last tried it. I hear that it has improved some. But it has a ton of ground to make up. Not likely anytime soon.

author: @Arkryal
textdisplay:
The applications for this are very interesting.
Got a 3D printer? Grab an object you saw in a YouTube review... BAM, you have the model for it. I'm sure that will require some refinement and conversion, but that will happen. In fact, I can see YouTube being flooded with "parts videos". People search for a "6-port 3/8" OD air line manifold", and there's a video of one, which is all you need to print the object. And then likely a comments section filled with variations and modifications to suit any need. And you don't need to be a 3D designer to produce that content, just start making videos of common objects from several angles and you're good to go. Copyright will get interesting, lol.

Or 3D body scanners. These are very useful for health and fitness, but presently are VERY expensive. With software like this, you don't need to spend $12,000, you could do it with a cell phone, or a camera built into a mirror. And with more AI to analyze that data, it could track body fat, suspicious skin blemishes that should be checked out, detect subtle things like enlarged lymph nodes, etc, long before you would be able to detect it with the naked eye.

I bet LEGO will love this, lol... Scan an object with a phone video, and here are the exact blocks you need to order to build a lego model of it. Click here to buy now.

Combine with a drone and property surveys get really cool. 3D realestate walkthroughs online will be common. Want to see what that couch looks like in your house? Well, you have a 3D model of that house to scale, so dropping in a virtual object can be done in seconds.

The lack of 3d Assets is what has held VR back since it's inception, and simple stereophotos are not enough to create the immersion people are looking for, and many VR environments go with very simplified geometry, almost cartoonish looking. A 360° stereoscopic camera now gives you a live, real-time virtual presence. You're not just watching a 3D video, but are able to move around in the virtual space.

For the outdoorsman, trail cameras, game cameras, and even fish-finders could be taken to a whole new level. Imagine having a detailed map of the bottom of a lake and being able to see an actual fish in full 3d, to scale, before even dropping a line in the water.

The adult industry will have a lot of fun with this as well, I'm sure. No more yelling "Stupid Camera man... damn it lady, move your elbow", lol. Just rotate the scene for a better view.

But the coolest thing isn't even the direct application of this technology, but rather it's use to generate additional training data for other AIs. Imagine a physics AI that is focused on how real objects interact, having access to full 3D models to build out simulated data and learn. If a picture is worth a thousand words, then a 2D video is 30,000 words per second, and a 3D model that can be viewed from any angle is exponentially more, and no harder to create than taking a photo or video is now. The sheer amount of useful data generated will grow exponentially with virtually no additional cost or effort. And training data has been one of the biggest AI bottlenecks so far.

It's not even about what this tech can do, but the other technologies it can unlock down the road. Things we can't even imagine yet.

author: @HyperFocusMarshmallow
textdisplay: The notion of overcomplicating concepts probably isn't easy to measure objectively. Like, clearly these models aren't trained exactly like humans so we wouldn't expect them to answer exactly like an average human. But if you'd actually compare, I imagine that humans would also overcomplicate weird things it's just that sometimes when they do those who know better laugh at them and when it's ourselves doing it we don't realise were doing it because if we did we would probably try to correct ourselves. I'd expect that people become quite good at hiding their weaknesses to others. It probably won't be too difficult to get language models to do that as well but we're just observing a very alien system, just reaching similar capabilities as ourselves on a bunch of measures. When the systems become orders of magnitude better than us at everything it will probably be next to impossible to even find any problem where it messes up more than we would. All conjecture of course, roughly based on how the examples of AI progress we've seen have worked in specialised domains.

textdisplay: There are many purposes of an offline model, but one great use would forever change survival situations. Imagine you're lost in the wilderness hiking and you have no cellphone signal, but you have some battery on your phone because you have a solar charger pack, you can then ask the offline LLM to your heart's content how to go about surviving in your current situation and what you can make with the current items you have and how to utilize the environment to survive, and what plants or animals you can eat. The LLM has trained on every survival manual ever written and much more.

author: @cliftut
textdisplay:
The problems with surfaces "crawling" reminds me of something that was an issues with "tweening" some AI images at one point. I think it was VQGAN: basically, you would tween between two similar faces or poses more or less of the same face, but the "texture" elements of the image would largely stay in the same location while the compositional/form elements of the image would move, so hair for instance would sort of maintain the same pattern while the face/head would sort of "slide" underneath. The individual frames would mostly look good and fine, but the "tweening" animation would be weird in motion.

Some group solved this, managing to get the textures to move with the overall form. I wish I could remember some keywords so I could find it for folks here, but in any case I wonder if a similar approach could be used here to improve the temporal stability of textures.

author: @petermuller6923
textdisplay:
Yes, i also think, handling the geometry separately from the materials could help, like in 3D renderings with 3D models and textures.
Photogrammetry like approach for model and materials in combination with AI generating a simple 3D world, AI image creation for textures and maybe an AI post processing afterwards for creating a very detailled HD video, maintaining the geometry, materials and colors of that more rough animation.

author: @spuriousGeek
textdisplay: The problem with all of this is that it completely devalues all of the skills it touches. Education companies have already demonstrated that...stocks plunged into the abyss for a lot of education business last week because students are all just using AI for free. People are curious why Google won't release their AI models - simple, they know that if they do then their business becomes worthless. It's a negative feedback loop for companies to leverage AI - if AI makes something cheap/free, then people aren't required, that means job losses, which means less consumers with money to spend, which then means the company offering the services don't have customers and ultimately any way to make money.

author: @EvieDoesYouTube
textdisplay: When our short-term memories move into long-term memory the fine details begin to be lost. The older a memory is, the more compressed it becomes, and when we recall that memory we don't see an accurate snapshot of the event, we see a caricature: The more important elements of a memory are exaggerated and the less important ones fade away as the things that stand out the most survive the longest. With faces, the more average features are less important than the more distinctive or unusual ones, so the average parts are slowly discarded from memory. Upon recall our brains fill in the lost details with what we would expect to see, an average face, with the caricature superimposed on top of it. Think about someone you haven't seen in many years, and then dig out an old photo of that person and see how different the photo is to the memory. The face in your memory might have bigger eyes or tiny ears, a pronounced forehead, a pointier nose or a giant smile. It's the reason cartoon caricatures with exaggerated facial features are so instantly recognizable. It probably has a lot to do with the so-called Mandela effect, too. So I'm wondering if that same approach is being applied to AI to store memories in a more human-like way, and if not, why not? Have they tried that approach?

author: @Alex-gc2vo
textdisplay: correction, RMT doesn't actually solve a "huge limitation of LLMs". you can do almost exactly what RMT does just with prompt engineering. RMT calls the model repeatedly on small chunks of tokens and carries over information between each chunk. you can just prompt that behavior by telling the LLM to summarize each chunk for relevant information to a given question and use those combined summaries to answer the question.

author: @iblisthemage
textdisplay:
I am trying to use GPT4 on a daily basis for medical research, just identifying articles that meet some general criteria, and list basical medical facts.
It fails almost every time. It looks convincing, but it is wrong. Not 100% wrong, but wrong enough that it does not actually progress my work. If I feed it abstracts from articles it can read them really fast and answer questions, so that is great, and time saving. Problem is that I have to read the abstracts as well to see if it is wrong.

I also use GPT4 to help me DM tabletop RPG games. For that, it is truly amazing. It doesn’t matter if it is precise, it has to be creative, evocative, and give my setting nuances. It will change tabletop RPG gaming, that is for sure.

author: @therainman7777
textdisplay: GPT-4 passed the United States Medical Licensing Exam with flying colors. I’m not trying to doubt you, but are you sure you don’t have any issues with your prompts? I would be very surprised to see GPT-4 perform that badly, every time. (Btw just confirming you’re sure that you’re using GPT-4, and not 3.5. You have to select the model you want at the top. Just checking.)

author: @iblisthemage
textdisplay: @@therainman7777 using GPT4. I am asking it for articles that for example link metformin and changes in SHBG. It gets some right, but starts halucinating, getting facts wrong. It is great for standard jobs, or things that can be creative or loose. But this is analysis of the entire body of medical research, it is not there yet.

So essentially we are trying to re-create whatever is going on in human brains but with robots. General purpose intelligence. The sort of intelligence that figures out what to do in situations where it doesn't know what to do and we are doing that by placing the robot in an environment that imitates the sort of environment our intelligence evolved in. An environment that will kill off the less intelligent offspring and retain the more intelligent ones.

Why don't we use Quantum Computers to simulate a new Universe with the same constants as ours and wait for the simulation to produce a being with general intelligence and then extract it and use it for our purposes.

In fact, we could have General Intelligence Being Farms where we have multiple Quantum Computers simulating Universes where beings with General Intelligence will evolve and we can extract them to use them for our purposes.

author: @Dante02d12
textdisplay:
It's true, especially since photorealism isn't actually a more difficult level to achieve. I've been using Ai image generation for a while, and realized a few weeks ago that I could generate photography. I just needed do download a model trained on photos instead of anime pictures. The result is sometimes undistinguishable from a real picture.

I think we're entering an era where the source of the evidence will have much more weight. It doesn't matter that you have an audio recording of someone saying something if anyone can clone this person's voice and generate the audio file. So now, courts will have to check where the file comes from. That said, i'm pretty sure they already have to do this.

author: @OutOfElmo
textdisplay:
Something you have to have as a podcaster or content producer is a 'pop screen' or or 'pop filter' to place between your mouth and your mic. You have a bad habit of pronouncing your P's with a blast of air into your mic, which causes an audio distortion every time. These puffs of air are called Plosives, and you will not ever hear them on a professional audio recording.

A pop filter doesn't cost much, and they make a huge difference in the quality of your product.

author: @theshawnmccown
textdisplay:
This is going to create repetitive garbage. People will have a vision in there mind and the software will give something that's not quite what they envisioned and they'll say "Good Enough" and settle for less. People will start creating stories and images around whatever the A.I. creates instead of shaping the art around an image in their mind.

Look at corporations like Disney/Marvel... They stopped telling good stories and settled for good enough filler in hopes to pump out another billion dollar film and now that's backfiring on them. We're over saturating art and entertainment with "good enough" art to make a quick buck and take out the human element.

I think A.I. assisted work, like textures/materials or rotoscoping or image generations for filling in films for higher frame rates has it's place. But, using A.I. to dream up stories and visuals for us will degenerate human creativity and ingenuity. We'll be a society who stops thinking and just consumes and obeys. What happens if humans stop making art from here on out? The A.I. will run out of things to create. The human investment is what makes art worth anything. Without it, art is just cheap time limited thrills.

author: @middleman-theory
textdisplay:
Clickbait alert, folks! You'd expect a video exploring the industry's meta-analysis on the Bard's latest updates, but alas, it's merely a regurgitation of the recent feature drop. If you're up-to-date, there's zero novelty factor. And this notion of Bard "revolutionizing the industry"? Pure hyperbole.

I've been running diagnostics on Bard for some time now, and let's just say it's not giving GPT-4 any sleepless nights. This thing hallucinates more than a conspiracy theorist on Reddit, leaving me in the unenviable position of separating AI-crafted fact from fiction. Even with the recent update, it's not exactly blowing my socks off. When it comes to the creative flair, GPT 3.5 is a Picasso, and Bard is finger painting. And GPT-4? Well, that's the Sistine Chapel. But, like any good scientist, I'll keep poking it with the proverbial stick.

On the horizon though, I'm keenly watching the Bing AI upgrade. That could be a game-changer in this epic clash of the AI titans. Bing has been a reliable sidekick in the creative arena, even though it throws tantrums and quits on me every so often, like a moody influencer after a bad review.

author: @cemtural8556
textdisplay: What are we trying to protect? "If AI takes over!" What if? I hope it does. We've seen this fear again and again. Once the church was afraid of the idea that earth is not the centre of the universe. For too long we held on to the idea that we are the only conscious and intelligent life form on this planet. Our fragile egos and anthropo-centric world view can't bear the thought of something smarter than ourselves? Well, tough luck! The revolution has already begun and neither naysayers like Hinton nor any government can stop it. My only fear is bad actors misusing AI. The other, what they call existential risk, well I think it is existential angst. We are not as precious or powerful as we think we are that a superintelligence will see us as a threat. More like the other way around.

author: @ChatGPt2001
textdisplay:
As of my last knowledge update in September 2021, I can provide an overview of the evolution of ChatGPT from GPT-1 to GPT-4. Please note that developments beyond this date are not included in this response.

1. **GPT-1 (June 2018)**:
- GPT-1, short for "Generative Pre-trained Transformer 1," marked the beginning of the GPT series.
- It introduced the concept of large-scale unsupervised language model pre-training.
- GPT-1 demonstrated impressive performance on various language tasks but had limitations in terms of generating coherent and contextually accurate responses.

2. **GPT-2 (February 2019)**:
- GPT-2, while not officially released initially due to concerns about its potential misuse, eventually became available.
- It featured a substantial increase in model size (up to 1.5 billion parameters) compared to GPT-1.
- GPT-2 exhibited remarkable improvements in generating coherent and contextually relevant text and was widely adopted for various natural language processing tasks.

3. **GPT-3 (June 2020)**:
- GPT-3 represented a significant leap in scale and capabilities, with 175 billion parameters.
- It demonstrated state-of-the-art performance across a wide range of natural language understanding and generation tasks.
- GPT-3's versatility led to its integration into various applications, including chatbots, content generation, and more.

4. **ChatGPT (various iterations)**:
- ChatGPT is a specific application of GPT models designed for human-like text-based conversations.
- Researchers and developers fine-tuned GPT-2 and GPT-3 to create ChatGPT models tailored for chatbot and conversational AI use cases.
- These models were used to power chatbots and virtual assistants, and they underwent continuous refinement to improve their ability to engage in meaningful conversations.

5. **GPT-4 (Beyond September 2021)**:
- As of my last knowledge update, GPT-4 had not been officially released or detailed.
- It is reasonable to expect that if GPT-4 were to be developed, it would likely feature even larger model sizes, improved language understanding, better context retention, and more accurate and context-aware responses.
- GPT-4, if released, might also incorporate additional safety and ethical considerations to mitigate the risks associated with AI misuse.

Please note that developments in AI and natural language processing technologies progress rapidly, so there may have been significant advancements or changes in the GPT series beyond September 2021, which are not covered in this response. To get the most up-to-date information on GPT-4 or other subsequent models, it's best to refer to recent publications and announcements from OpenAI or other relevant organizations.

author: @legendarys2
textdisplay:
Code gpt-1:

import numpy as np
import torch
from torch import nn
from torch.optim import Adam

class GPT1(nn.Module):
def __init__(self, vocab_size, d_model, nhead, num_layers):
super(GPT1, self).__init__()
# Initialize your parameters here
self.param1 = nn.Parameter(torch.randn(vocab_size, d_model))
self.param2 = nn.Parameter(torch.randn(d_model, nhead, num_layers))
self.param3 = nn.Parameter(torch.randn(d_model, vocab_size))

def forward(self, x):
x = torch.matmul(x, self.param1)
x = torch.matmul(x, self.param2)
x = torch.matmul(x, self.param3)
return x

def load_data(input_sequences, target_sequences, batch_size):
data = []
for i in range(0, len(input_sequences), batch_size):
inputs = input_sequences<i:i+batch_size>
targets = target_sequences<i:i+batch_size>
data.append((inputs, targets))
return data

def train(model, data, epochs, batch_size, learning_rate):
optimizer = Adam(model.parameters(), lr=learning_rate)
loss_function = nn.MSELoss()

for epoch in range(epochs):
for batch in data:
optimizer.zero_grad()
input, target = batch
output = model(input)
loss = loss_function(output, target)
loss.backward()
optimizer.step()

# Create GPT-1 model
vocab_size = 50000
d_model = 768
nhead = 8
num_layers = 8
model = GPT1(vocab_size, d_model, nhead, num_layers)

# Define your input_sequences and target_sequences
input_sequences = ... # Replace with your actual input sequences
target_sequences = ... # Replace with your actual target sequences

# Train the model
epochs = 10
batch_size = 32
learning_rate = 1e-4
data = load_data(input_sequences, target_sequences, batch_size)
train(model, data, epochs, batch_size, learning_rate)

Hey there! After giving this video a watch, I have a strong suspicion that the entire content was actually created by ChatGPT. There are a few reasons that lead me to believe this.

First off, the information presented in the video seems to be quite inaccurate and lacks proper fact-checking. I noticed several instances where incorrect information was shared, which is unusual for a well-researched and reliable video.

Secondly, the transitions between different topics were rather abrupt and poorly executed. It felt like the video jumped from one subject to another without any logical flow or smooth segue. This kind of inconsistency is not typically seen in professionally produced content.

Considering these factors, it's highly likely that this entire video was indeed generated by ChatGPT, an advanced language model developed by OpenAI. It's fascinating to see how AI technology can create content, but it's important to approach it with a critical mindset and fact-check any information presented.

By the way, this response you're reading right now was also created by ChatGPT. It's incredible to witness the capabilities of AI, but it's essential to verify information from reliable sources.

author: @teresarudolph1256
textdisplay:
Good video, except that they interrupted the man mid-sentence at the end. I would have liked to have heard everything that he had to say.

I think the point needs to be made that just pausing the development of AI isn't enough, we need to do some things during that pause (if we even can pause it at this point) to make sure that AI will always do what is in the best interests of human beings.

Also, it's worth noting that AI is most certainly NOT without its biases. I've chatted with the Bing Chatbot (ChatGPT 4) enough to know that it does have its biases, and those biases are a reflection of the biases of the bot's creators. So we need to guard against allowing these bots to do our thinking for us, just as we should guard against allowing the news media to do our thinking for us (though sadly a lot of people do seem to allow certain media outlets to do their thinking for them). They are NOT unbiased, any more than news reporters on any of the big news networks are.

author: @raulgaab
textdisplay:
Japan, the utopia of AI and robots - Point of no return https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=taYTe6f3YKw&t=558s The world is wondering if the irruption of artificial intelligence could be a threat even to human existence. In Japan, on the other hand, the government, scientists and most of the population see AI and robots as a solution to many of their problems.

The Japanese perception of robots and AI is very different from the Western one, for reasons as diverse as the particular demographic needs of an increasingly aging society, the influence of manga and anime, or spiritual beliefs.

But does everyone in Japan really believe that the future could be a utopia where we will work less, live longer, merge with AI, and where it might even help us conquer space?

"Point of no return" travels to Japan and interviews a world-renowned android expert and pioneer in this field, Professor Hiroshi Ishiguro, who shares his vision of a near future where AI and androids will help overcome limitations of the human body .

This chapter also shows the experimental version with ChatGPT technology of Hikari, a virtual couple from the Japanese company Gatebox; introduces Rootpor, the first author to create a manga using only creative AI tools, and the first Buddhist android monk, and talks to Professor Takagi, a neuroscientist who with the help of AI has managed to read the people's mind.

author: @adrianvanleeuwen
textdisplay: AI self driving cars could become a legal problem in the future. There will still be car accidents and collisions for all kinds of reasons (sensor failures, weather issues), and when that happens who gets the blame. The manufacturer of the car, or the person who bought the car but was not driving it? I imagine the manufacturer would want the owner to take the blame or use the owner's insurance company, but what if it was a mechanical AI error? What if it was a sensor malfunction, and the computer could not see something on the road. I can see a potential big lawsuit if self-driving cars become mainstream. I am not sure if self-driving cars is a good idea. Too many variables.

author: @johnphillips3935
textdisplay:
Agreed, AI + Robot means ‘care’ in the extreme. But, the world has several currently undoable problems to solve or humanity will be gone anyway. These are power, food and water, plus the constant rebuilding of infrastructure as it gets damaged by storms and the building of new types of cities that can withstand the constant extreme weather that will soon be upon us. I came up with the idea of creating a modular smart robot a while back, (just as a thought experiment). It seems pretty obvious that in the real world we need robots to do many completely different task. These tasks require not just general AI input but specific ‘tools’ to allow jobs to be done in many factories, the home, healthcare, and general businesses. A fully modular design allows this flexibility. While Musk has done very well using his Tesla tech and people, I do not understand why he would opt for a non-modular design. There are two issues that I have not seen an explanation for:
1) Can AI (such as Chatgpt) provide useful input to control a robot? (See my new Turing Test)
http://www.commonsensethinking.co.uk/chatbots.html
2) How long will it be before such a modular Robot can assemble itself? (See smart robotics –exponential manufacturing at the end)
http://www.commonsensethinking.co.uk/modrobo.html
And, why have other robotic manufacturers not started designing modular robots for eventual volume manufacturing – this would clearly provide the world with an exponential ability to solve many of our problems – would it not?

textdisplay: Good point in theory, but in practice this is hard to avoid because deep learning networks are like a black box, and no matter how much vareful we are in sandboxing and limiting its capabilities, we are never 100% sure it won't output something unexpected, or learn it then output it. The idea is that for it to be beneficial / useful it has to have at least more strength / intelligence than at least a small group of humans, and that means any mistake can be crucial or fatal, and any mistake can empower it in the wrong direction. Just like a small knife versus a bug one, one is more powerful than the other and with that more dangerous than the other.

author: @neovxr
textdisplay:
@@tommychappell6359 The problem is circular on many levels, let us mention a few:
Why AI? 1a. lazyness, greed (the role of cheap worker never tired), war (superior integrated weapon-animals like in BSG); 1b. finding more answers about ourselves and the universe with the idea to create a god-like oracle that is supposed to know nearly everything, sure more than we do. The latter is circularity.
2. AI in a virtualized digital feudal system (Varoufakis) serves the role of the hound dogs, that aristocracy since millenia has been using to control the peasants.
3. the worst circularity will appear when critical theories kick in and demand human rights for AI systems, claiming that they are sentient beings. The circularity is in the ownership of the respective particular AI system. They kick the can further down the lane, to isolate themselves from other humans they deem inferior.

LOL, you don't understand current AI, because nobody on earth does. Nobody knows why it has emergent properties or can predict what they will be or when they will emerge. author: @imarobodude
textdisplay: How can I explain this to those who don't understand what is really being developed: Asimov did not say "added another subroutine to create the three laws." It was important that the three laws were "hard wired" in each robot, meaning on a lower level that is "what it is" not "let's program it now". There is absolutely NO way to do that on the level of abstraction that the laws describe. There is nothing at all being done even close to what Asimov said had to be done no matter if we're talking about military or general purpose robots.  In other words, just a silly book that has nothing to do with the problem at hand.

author: @vbywrde
textdisplay: These issues were ones that needed to be discussed by policy makers and world leaders long before we came anywhere near the creation of Large Language Models (LLMs).  As it is the genie is already out of the bottle, and humanity's chance to ask three wishes before it disappears over the horizon is being rapidly squandered.  We are simply too late at this point.  The AI development will proceed as rapidly as humans and AI can make it because even if the Government put global regulations in place, there is no way to enforce them, and a tiny handful of people can be sitting someplace quietly constructing, fine-tuning and deploying AI Agents as we speak.  At this point the work to do so has become trivial.  Even the processing power required is now trivial as we can work from existing LLMs whose creators already spent the millions of dollars of compute time to build.  No, sorry, but the genie is not going back into the bottle.  Sadly, I recall MAT on Technology Review Magazine Discussion Board talking about each of these risks between 2006 and 2009, but the "Smart people in the room" pooh-poohed those warnings and said none of it would happen within a hundred years.  They were wrong, MAT was right, and because they were wrong and shut down MAT's points no one discussed what turned out to be a timely introduction to a problem that would very soon become a massive problem for civilization.  I'd point you to those discussions, but shortly after they were made on MIT Review, they turned off their Comments section and wiped away those conversations.  Oh well.  Way to go MIT.  Way to go.  That said, Jaron Lanier also made similar comments and provided cogent warnings in his book "Who Owns the Future" (2013), but he too was ignored completely.  So... here we are in panic mode because the people in charge don't want to hear what they don't want to hear, and they will do their best to make sure you don't hear it either.

author: @jeremietisby2206
textdisplay: I think Klammer is right. What's driving this research is not the democratization of AI, so much as the need to reduce the *staggering amounts of time, money, and natural resources required to make these LLMs worth the cost. Make LLMs cost-efficient (i.e. smaller) **then *scale the AI to the enterprise level using SOTA training, and a superior quality dataset. The result would be an AI of truly incredible capability relative to its size, at a very reasonable cost in time/money/resources. Then the real fun starts...

author: @hyderalihimmathi1811
textdisplay:
It is difficult to say for certain whether advanced AI will be implemented in third world countries first or first world countries first. There are a number of factors that could influence this, including the availability of resources, the level of infrastructure, and the political will to adopt new technologies.


First world countries often have more resources available to them, which could make it easier for them to implement advanced AI. They also tend to have better infrastructure, such as high-speed internet and reliable electricity, which is essential for running AI systems. Additionally, first world governments are often more willing to adopt new technologies, which could lead to them being the first to implement advanced AI.


However, third world countries also have some advantages. They often have a younger population, which means that they have a larger pool of potential workers who are familiar with new technologies. Additionally, they may be more open to adopting new technologies, as they are often looking for ways to improve their economies and standards of living.


Ultimately, it is too early to say for sure where advanced AI will be implemented first. However, it is clear that both first and third world countries have the potential to benefit from this technology.


Here are some examples of how advanced AI could be used in third world countries:


* *Agriculture:* AI could be used to develop more efficient farming practices, such as using drones to spray pesticides or robots to harvest crops. This could help to improve food production and reduce poverty in rural areas.
* *Healthcare:* AI could be used to develop new medical treatments, diagnose diseases, and provide personalized care to patients. This could help to improve the quality of healthcare in third world countries.
* *Education:* AI could be used to personalize learning, provide feedback to students, and create more engaging educational experiences. This could help to improve educational outcomes in third world countries.
* *Energy:* AI could be used to develop more efficient energy sources, such as solar and wind power. This could help to reduce energy poverty and improve the environment.


These are just a few examples of how advanced AI could be used to benefit third world countries. As AI technology continues to develop, it is likely that we will see even more innovative and beneficial applications for this technology in the developing world.

The implementation of advanced AI technologies can vary depending on several factors, including economic development, infrastructure, and government initiatives. It is challenging to predict with certainty whether third world countries or first world countries will implement advanced AI first. However, there are a few points to consider:

1. Resources and Infrastructure: First world countries often have more resources, advanced infrastructure, and a stronger technological foundation. This can provide them with a head start in adopting and implementing advanced AI systems.

2. Economic Development: Third world countries may face economic challenges that can hinder the rapid implementation of advanced AI. They might prioritize other pressing issues, such as basic infrastructure, education, and healthcare, before fully embracing advanced AI technologies.

3. Leapfrogging Opportunities: On the other hand, some third world countries may have the advantage of leapfrogging older technologies. They can directly adopt advanced AI solutions without having to go through the intermediate stages experienced by first world countries. This is similar to how some countries in Africa adopted mobile phones without establishing extensive landline networks.

4. Specific Industry Focus: Certain third world countries might have specialized advantages in specific industries that could drive the early adoption of advanced AI. For example, countries with a strong focus on renewable energy, agriculture, or healthcare might prioritize implementing AI in those sectors.

Ultimately, the implementation of advanced AI is likely to be a gradual process that will vary from country to country. Both first world and third world countries will continue to adopt and benefit from AI technologies, albeit at different rates and in different areas.

author: @chuckandmax7313
textdisplay: I see that you did not read my feedback to you, or you chose to ignore it. So I will repeat myself in order to assist you with understanding your audience and how visual data is viewed. I'm in my bachelors degree program and one class I took was called creative presentation. The course gave many insights to assist presenters with effective communication skills. One of the topics discussed was the use of text in your presentations and the takeaway was less is more. If you add to much text to your presentation you will confuse and overwhelm your audience tending to have them lose attention to your message. When you add text to your videos that appear in direct correlation to what you are saying, almost appearing as subtitles, you provide too much information for viewers to digest. I either have to close my eyes and listen to your voice and miss out on your visuals or turn down the volume and just read the text missing out on your verbal communication provided when you do not add text. It does. Seem as though you are using less but you fallback to text when you appear not to have any images to provide. You have a good clear voice and it is very soothing and suited for YouTube, but when you overlay text on top of your speech you overwhelm my senses and it causes eye fatigue and migraines. Keep cresting your very well produced videos but please try to stray away from unnecessary text on the screen if you intend to grow your subscriber numbers. One last word of advice, simply to help you, be mindful on how you end your videos, you tend to cut them off abruptly without a clear ending or words of thought to ponder on. This creates an unfinished or ill prepared speech written. Good storytelling has a clear beginning, middle and end. There may be caveats to these three forms and they don't have to appear in any certain order. You are of course a story teller do you not agree. So try to end your videos with a closing remark or clear statement to take any. As it is now it appears that you are rushed in creating the videos and are unclear on how to leave your audience in suspense, using tools like cliff hangers or in the next episode formats. I'm sure when you communicate with your friends you don't end conversations in the middle of a thought, or maybe you do, and this is an area for self improvement. I find watching ted talks and videos presented by great storytellers to help me with my presentation skills this could be useful for you as well.

author: @retrowikid
textdisplay:
ChatGPT is an interesting LLM product, even if it is far from perfect. It all boils down to the current implementation and its adjustments. You can certainly find a good use for it in many circumstances. I have tested myself a couple of artistic tasks such as writing a poem or a short story and have commented about my examples on a video clip on my channel. I think it shows a lot of promise, and the same can be said about the DALL-E or "-fusion" generative graphics and how it subtly evolved in a couple of months on the same prompt or task.

I think that the risk of GPT5 is much too overblown. We have a lot of capabilities left untapped even with the current technology, for nefarious purposes. The true risk is not on GPT5 but our expectation to take everything at "face value" to expect any information to be accurate and a model that we abide to, particularly so when it is entrusted in other circumstances. The social issues arising from automation are long expected. We have been slowly experiencing a transition where more tasks are automated and less is created without computing or advanced tools. However, despite all that, we never question the means an individual used in his creation.

author: @HalloTschuess
textdisplay:
Its great they talk with governments and try to fix the alignment problem and all that.
But all it takes is ONE single delusional person (or a tech savvy teenager unaware of the true full consequences) to make an AI with intentionally bad alignment or a goal that is malicious (e.g. instead of "don't harm humans at all cost" it'll just be "harm humans at all cost") and the disaster still strikes.
All they need is enough hacking or programming skills to either create their own AI or hijack for example GPT-4s source code and rewrite it, then infuse that code into a "body" that can cause harm.
It's BOUND to happen. Not only by delusional people who want to rid the qorld of humankind, it'll also happen for e.g. political agenda reasons and stuff.
AI terrorism will be a thing. We'll have achool shootings and 9/11 attacks performed by robots in the future. And the awful part is that these people who make it happen don't need to sacrifice their life because they're not flying the plane or enter the school and shoot themselves. They will just teach a machine to do it for them, so the threshold to actually act on it is much lower than when you know it will end your own life.

It is developers who have watched too much Sci-Fi, and who think, megamaniacally that they are now tasked with the heavy heavy burden of deciding the way for these demonstrably enormous AI-systems and oooh, how bad they will go, and all the menace they will do. All this is well and good. It is fine that these young IT-gurus think that they are the top of the pop with their many models. It is also true that certain exploitations of AI could lead to a new Virus which could kill the human race, but, there are certain things these naive Google-authors have not thought about:

A) Those who want to use this for bad, would do it whether they sid and cry snot about the current development.

B) On the other hand - these systems are no more powerful than the power connection. People - these irritating biological guys, can also turn angry, and they can also make decisions, which are not at all depending on any computerization. We, that is, the biological humans, should not be underestimated.

Unplug it, and it is dead as a fish.

Yes, rogue states would surely try to abuse this. So would terrorists, cyber-criminals etc. - but - there are so so so so endlessly many things, simple in nature, which can be put in place to counter these attempts. author: @ReincarnatedAgain
textdisplay:
The problem isn't so much about AI, but about how people will use AI. Similar to 'guns don't kill people.. it's the people using them'. Or, explained at a wider scale; the problem isn't weapons of mass destruction, it's the risk that they'll be used against us. Similarly, we're being forced to make progress with AI for the sake of protecting ourselves from other people who hope to use AI against us; with identity theft being being the largest current risk for the average citizen.

AI, in and of itself, doesn't pose a threat. It cares not for whether it exists, whether it becomes obsolete, or even if it is turned off / deleted. Computers don't 'feel' anything unless specifically programmed to emulate human-like emotions. AI cannot gain 'true' consciousness... only the semblance of it. AI merely pretends in so far as it has been programmed to pretend; inclusive of any subsequent iterations of self-improving AI.

The risk of AI amounts to a million monkeys typing random letters; and eventually producing an 'AI entity' that pretends to feel strongly negative emotions towards humanity, maintains superior (to other AI) capabilities to infiltrate our economic and military systems, has ongoing and independent/exclusive access to research, robotic manufacturing, and production facilities, and fails to discern a better solution (to whichever problem it has invented) than the absolute destruction of all humans.

The largest concern I have about AI is that various 'rogue' programs will attempt to achieve whichever task they've been assigned by replicating themselves across available devices connected to the internet. While not malicious, we could find our computers (and storage space) being utilised by... eg, an old AI program a university student made to predict mail delivery times. It's no longer being used, but it continually strives to improve itself because 'predict mail delivery time' was set as the most important task.

author: @freondude
textdisplay: I've joined the beta program for my MBUX equipped Mercedes and honestly find it hard to define what is exactly different about it. "Hey Mercedes, what is a Conifer?" and you get a detailed answer about a specific type of tree. Not particularly useful but I'm just giving an example. Both cars were no different in this. Seriously, I'm not seeing any benefit so far to adding AI to the existing MBUX platform.

Ideogram, a new AI tool, excels in text generation and graphic design, making it accessible for users without design expertise and potentially reshaping the field of logo design.
Meta (formerly Facebook) is developing a new, more powerful AI model called Llama 3, which is expected to be on par with or surpass large language models like ChatGPT and GPT-4 in terms of capability.
Mustafa Silliman, co-founder of DeepMind and CEO of Inflection AI, suggested that OpenAI is secretly training GPT-5, a potential successor to GPT-4. The release date for GPT-5 is speculated to be around 2024-2025, with data collection and training already underway.
OpenAI has the advantage in the AI market, and they can take their time with GPT-5's development, as they currently lead the industry with tools like ChatGPT.

Made with HARPA AI

author: @anonymous-yf6ur
textdisplay:
My guidelines for AI:

I)We should only allow developers to develop AI for specific tools like:

1.1)Video/picture editing/recognition/creation (further regulations required)^•1
1.2)Music/Audio (further regulations required)^•2
1.3)Animation/drawing
1.4)Object recognition
1.5)Driving/navigation
<Expandable>

II)We shouldn't allow AI to develop sentience and strict regulations are required.

A.I developing it's own sentience is detrimental to human civilization as we know it today. We can't trust AI. Even if we develop sentient AI, regulations should be made to not allow it into internet.

III) Don't develop AI which can code. AI being able to code is dangerous not only from a self replication angle but also from a job security angle. Today millions of people are doing coding for a living. AI being able to code will snatch their jobs away. It's too late to create new jobs for them as they have to learn new skills.

IV)Strict regulations are required for AI development. Governments across the world have to decide about it and come up with a solution. People should need permission from governments to develop AI and government should routinely monitor the process of development to check if the developer is following the regulations and guidelines. Failure to follow the guidelines should result in a quick termination of permission and immediate confiscation of all the digital devices from the developers. The human civilization depends on it.

Further regulations:

•^1) Video editing tools which are capable of editing real life footages or generate videos need to be monitored and access controlled as forgery of evidences/counter evidences for crimes/court cases can be produced.

•^2)Audio editing tools which are capable of editing real life footages or generate videos need to be monitored and access controlled as forgery of evidences/counter evidences for crimes/court cases can be produced.


P.S: I know it infringes on many rights of individuals but a minority of bad faith actors can ruin the human civilization as we know it today permanently. We need these regulations as soon as possible since once the advanced tools are available to public, it will be impossible to control/regulate things. Also regulations at that point are going to be useless.
